{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-808f1bf86f9c8a18","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tStoryTeller: Training-Free Narrative Grounding\n2\tfor Long-Form Audio Description\n3\tSeung Hyun Hahm, Minh T. Dinh, and SouYoung Jin\n4\t\n5\tarXiv:2607.11798v1 [cs.CV] 13 Jul 2026\n6\t\n7\tDartmouth College, USA\n8\t{Seung.Hyun.Hahm.GR,Minh.T.Dinh.GR,SouYoung.Jin}@dartmouth.edu\n9\t\n10\tAbstract. Long-form audio description (AD) requires more than describing visible actions: it must preserve characters, events, relationships,\n11\tand story context across scenes so that blind and low-vision (BLV) audiences can follow a film. Modern video–language models (VLMs) are effective on short clips, but they often treat each moment independently, producing descriptions that miss who characters are, why events matter, and\n12\thow the current scene connects to earlier narrative context. We propose\n13\tStoryTeller, a training-free framework for story-aware long-form AD. Instead of relying only on local visual cues, StoryTeller maintains a verified\n14\tnarrative memory that carries forward story-relevant information across\n15\tscenes, enabling later descriptions to remain coherent, grounded, and\n16\tcontextually informative. Given only raw video and a movie title, StoryTeller can optionally retrieve public movie metadata to resolve names\n17\tand story context, while accepting only facts that are supported by the\n18\tvideo through semantic filtering and VLM verification. The method requires no subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, aligned captions, character\n19\tbanks, precomputed face identities, or task-specific fine-tuning. To evaluate whether generated AD preserves narrative information, we introduce\n20\tStoryAD-QA1 , a question-answering benchmark that tests whether a\n21\tlanguage model can answer story-context questions using only the generated descriptions. Experiments on standard AD benchmarks and diverse\n22\tlong-form videos show that StoryTeller consistently improves narrative\n23\tcoherence, factual grounding, and story comprehension over strong baselines in automatic, QA-based, and human evaluations.\n24\tKeywords: audio description · long-form video understanding ·\n25\tretrieval-augmented generation · narrative grounding · accessibility\n26\t\n27\t1\n28\t\n29\tIntroduction\n30\t\n31\tAudio description (AD) enables blind and low-vision (BLV) audiences to access\n32\tvisual media by narrating important visual information between dialogue and\n33\tother sounds. Effective AD goes beyond describing objects or actions in the\n34\tcurrent frame: it identifies who is present, explains what has just happened,\n35\t1\n36\t\n37\tStoryAD-QA benchmark dataset and evaluation code:\n38\thttps://github.com/SEE-AI-Lab/ECCV2026_StoryTeller_StoryAD_QA\n39\t\n40\t\f2\n41\t\n42\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n43\tBaseline\n44\tAD\n45\t\n46\tAlbus Dumbledore makes his wand move with a flick of his wrist\n47\twhile conversing with someone. Harry is hit by a teacher,\n48\twhile Ron and Hermione look on.\n49\t\n50\tPrevious scene\n51\t\n52\tAlastor Mad\n53\tEye Moody\n54\tA professor at\n55\tHogwarts\n56\t\n57\tIdentity Graph\n58\t\n59\tSubject: boy\n60\tAction: covers\n61\tObject: hair\n62\tLocation: a desk\n63\t\n64\tObserved Fact\n65\t\n66\tSubject: Mad Eye Moody\n67\tAction: holds\n68\tObject: a spider\n69\tLocation: room with a chalkboard\n70\t\n71\tMemory\n72\t\n73\tStoryTeller Mad Eye Moody presents a spider to the class.\n74\tAD\n75\tA boy covers his head as a spider crawls on it.\n76\t\n77\tFig. 1: Story-level audio description requires narrative memory. Existing audio description (AD) systems typically generate descriptions using only local visual\n78\tcontext or static character banks, which often fails to preserve long-range narrative\n79\trelationships. Our StoryTeller instead maintains a persistent narrative state consisting of an identity graph that tracks characters across scenes and a salience-weighted\n80\tmemory that accumulates narrative facts over time. This enables consistent character\n81\treferences and long-range story reasoning across an entire film. The baseline example\n82\tis the output of AutoAD-Zero.\n83\t\n84\tconveys why a moment matters, and connects the scene to the broader narrative.\n85\tProfessional AD writers are able to provide this narrative grounding because\n86\tthey watch the film and write with the whole story in mind. However, producing\n87\thigh-quality AD remains costly and time-intensive, and copyright restrictions\n88\tmake large publicly distributable AD datasets difficult to obtain.\n89\tRecent advances in video–language models (VLMs) [2,19,30,36] and large language models have motivated research on automatic AD generation. State-of-theart identity-aware AD systems [8,9,27] are typically trained as task-specific models on curated movie datasets such as LSMDC [28] and MAD [31]. These pipelines\n90\tincorporate identity-aware components built from face-recognition backbones\n91\ttrained on labeled data. While effective in benchmark settings, this reliance on\n92\tcopyrighted training data, curated movie annotations, and specialized identity\n93\tmodules limits their scalability, reproducibility, and applicability to new films.\n94\tTraining-free pipelines, including AutoAD-Zero [38] and MM_Narrator [40],\n95\thave recently emerged as an alternative to supervised AD generation. These\n96\tmethods remove the need for task-specific model training, but they often still\n97\trely on resources prepared before AD generation, including character banks,\n98\taligned subtitles, or existing AD transcripts. Moreover, they typically propagate\n99\tcontext in shallow or static forms, such as concatenating previous descriptions\n100\tor reusing fixed identity features. Although these strategies can improve local\n101\tconsistency across nearby clips, they do not explicitly model how narrative in-\n102\t\n103\t\fStoryTeller\n104\t\n105\t3\n106\t\n107\tformation evolves over time: which characters, relationships, and events should\n108\tremain salient, and which details should fade as the film progresses.\n109\tHuman viewers do not understand a film by retaining a complete list of previous frames. Instead, they maintain an evolving representation of the story,\n110\twhere central characters, unresolved conflicts, and recurring relationships remain salient, while incidental visual details gradually lose importance. This perspective suggests that long-form AD should preserve identity continuity, causal\n111\tstructure, and evolving character interactions across a film, without relying on\n112\texternal resources such as subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, character banks, or\n113\tprecomputed face identities.\n114\tWe introduce StoryTeller, a training-free framework for long-form AD that\n115\tmaintains an explicit story state as it processes clips in chronological order. Given\n116\ta sequence of video clips {v1 , . . . , vT }, the system keeps two forms of memory:\n117\tan identity graph for recurring characters and a salience-weighted memory for\n118\tverified story facts. Each new clip updates this state through three steps: track\n119\tvisible identities, extract candidate facts with optional public movie metadata,\n120\tand verify those facts against the video before updating memory. The memory\n121\tthen reinforces facts that remain relevant and decays facts that no longer matter.\n122\tStoryTeller takes as input only the raw video and a movie title. The title\n123\tmay be used to retrieve public IMDb plot summaries, character lists, and short\n124\tcharacter descriptions. This retrieved text is only a source of possible names or\n125\tcontext; it is not copied into the AD, stored directly as memory, or treated as\n126\tground truth. A fact enters memory only if it is supported by the current clip\n127\tand accepted by semantic filtering and VLM verification.\n128\tBeyond generation, we also address evaluation. Standard metrics such as\n129\tBLEU [25], CIDEr [34], and SPICE [1] measure lexical overlap between generated\n130\tdescriptions and reference captions, but they do not evaluate whether a listener\n131\tcan reconstruct the narrative from the AD alone. To address this limitation, we\n132\tintroduce StoryAD-QA, a narrative-comprehension question-answering benchmark. For each scene, we generate questions whose answers depend on both\n133\tthe current clip and preceding narrative context. During evaluation, a language\n134\tmodel receives only the generated audio descriptions and must answer these\n135\tquestions without access to the video. This protocol directly measures whether\n136\tthe description preserves characters, events, and causal relationships necessary\n137\tfor story understanding rather than merely describing visual details in isolation.\n138\tContributions.\n139\t– We propose StoryTeller, a fully training-free framework for long-form audio\n140\tdescription that uses raw video and public title-keyed metadata without\n141\tsubtitles, AD transcripts, manually curated visual character banks, or taskspecific fine-tuning.\n142\t– We introduce an explicit narrative memory mechanism with reinforcement–\n143\tdecay dynamics that approximates how human viewers track evolving story\n144\tsalience across scenes.\n145\t\n146\t\f4\n147\t\n148\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n149\t\n150\t– We present StoryAD-QA, a narrative-comprehension QA benchmark that\n151\tevaluates whether generated audio descriptions support story understanding\n152\tbeyond lexical similarity.\n153\t\n154\t2\n155\t\n156\tRelated Work\n157\t\n158\tBenchmarking Audio Description Generation. Movie understanding has\n159\toften been studied as question answering over long videos [13, 32, 33, 35, 39].\n160\tFor example, MovieQA [33] uses questions grounded in plot summaries, scripts,\n161\tand subtitles, while [35] and [13] annotate characters, interactions, and story\n162\tstructure. MovieChat [32] emphasizes on long-video QA with sparse memory\n163\tand introduces MovieChat-1K. These datasets are crucial for evaluating video\n164\treasoning, but they do not directly ask whether an AD gives a listener enough\n165\tinformation to understand the story without seeing the video.\n166\tDatasets designed specifically for AD instead focus on localized narration.\n167\tLSMDC [28] and MAD [31] provide large-scale movie captioning resources\n168\taligned to short clips, and recent AD generation systems [8–10, 26, 27, 38, 40]\n169\tbuild on these datasets with identity-aware modules or curated character banks.\n170\tDespite their usefulness, evaluation in these works often relies on direct string\n171\tcomparison with professional AD using metrics such as CIDEr [34], SPICE [1],\n172\tand ROUGE [21], which are highly sensitive to temporal alignment. Addressing\n173\tthis limitation, AutoAD II [8] introduces an evaluation protocol that measures\n174\twhether generated descriptions are semantically aligned with nearby groundtruth annotations rather than requiring exact sentence matches. Building on this\n175\tdirection, AutoAD III [10] further proposes CRITIC for evaluating character\n176\tretrieval and LLM-AD-Eval for sentence-level semantic scoring with LLMs.\n177\tMore recently, question-answering evaluation has been explored to assess\n178\tthe usefulness of AD. ADQA [15] evaluates whether generated AD supports\n179\tvisual appreciation and narrative understanding in a certain video segment via\n180\tquestions generated from reference descriptions. Instead, our benchmark focuses\n181\ton long-form narrative grounding, evaluating whether ADs preserve information\n182\trequired for reasoning over story context that spans multiple scenes.\n183\tIdentity Modeling in Video Narratives. Maintaining consistent character\n184\tidentity across scenes is essential for long-form video understanding and AD. Several recent AD systems explicitly rely on character banks–precomputed repositories of character-specific visual features, e.g., face embeddings or reference images\n185\tused to recognize recurring characters throughout a movie [8–10]. In contrast,\n186\tStoryTeller requires no character bank or precomputed face identities. Instead, it\n187\tdiscovers recurring identities directly from repeated face observations, allowing\n188\tcharacter identities to emerge dynamically as narrative evidence accumulates.\n189\tRetrieval-Augmented Generation. Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)\n190\timproves grounding by incorporating external evidence during generation [5,\n191\t18]. However, naive retrieval can introduce irrelevant or contradictory information and may amplify hallucinations in multimodal models [12, 29]. Prior\n192\twork improves retrieval quality through dense retrievers and structured fusion\n193\t\n194\t\fStoryTeller\n195\t\n196\t5\n197\t\n198\tmechanisms [7, 14, 16], but these approaches focus primarily on factual knowledge grounding rather than narrative coherence. Our approach instead performs\n199\tnarrative-aware retrieval restricted to movie-scoped sources and triggered only\n200\twhen scene observations indicate potentially story-relevant events.\n201\tMemory for Long-Horizon Reasoning. Memory mechanisms have been\n202\twidely explored for long-horizon multimodal reasoning. Recent systems such\n203\tas VideoAgent [4], Optimus-1 [20], and M3-Agent [23] maintain explicit temporal memories to support extended video reasoning. Other long-video systems\n204\temploy episodic memories for VideoQA [37], retrieval-augmented memories for\n205\tlong-video comprehension [24], or global audio-visual character representations\n206\tfor dense video description [11]. These methods primarily target long-video QA,\n207\tembodied reasoning, video comprehension, or dense video description. In contrast, StoryTeller is designed for accessibility-oriented audio description, where\n208\tgenerated descriptions are intended to complement the original movie audio\n209\trather than summarize the entire film. Instead of maintaining a general-purpose\n210\tmemory, StoryTeller stores a lightweight narrative memory of visually verified\n211\tstory facts with evolving salience weights, allowing important characters and\n212\tevents to persist across scenes while transient details gradually fade.\n213\t\n214\t3\n215\t\n216\tStoryTeller\n217\t\n218\tFigure 2 illustrates the overall pipeline of StoryTeller. The input is a movie\n219\tdivided into chronological clips {v1 , . . . , vT }. StoryTeller processes the clips sequentially while carrying a persistent narrative state that summarizes story information accumulated from previously processed clips. This state enables the\n220\tsystem to track recurring characters, extract scene-level events, and preserve\n221\tlong-range narrative context throughout the movie.\n222\tBefore processing clip vt , the system maintains the narrative state\n223\t  \\mathcal {S}_{t-1} = (\\mathcal {G}_{t-1}, \\mathcal {M}_{t-1}), \n224\t\n225\t(1)\n226\t\n227\twhere Gt−1 is the identity graph storing visual representations of recurring\n228\tcharacters, and Mt−1 is the narrative memory storing verified story facts together with their salience weights.\n229\tProcessing clip vt updates the narrative state according to\n230\t  \\mathcal {S}_{t} = \\Phi (v_t, \\mathcal {S}_{t-1}), \n231\t\n232\t(2)\n233\t\n234\twhere Φ denotes the overall state update operator.\n235\tFor each new clip, StoryTeller updates its narrative state through three modules. First, the identity graph update links visible faces to existing character\n236\tnodes when there is sufficient visual evidence, allowing the system to maintain\n237\tconsistent references to recurring characters across clips. Second, grounded fact\n238\tinduction proposes structured facts about the current scene, optionally using\n239\tpublic movie metadata as hints for names or story context. These candidate\n240\tfacts are then filtered to ensure that they are semantically relevant to the scene\n241\t\n242\t\f6\n243\t\n244\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n245\tMovie-Scoped\n246\tRetrieval\n247\t\n248\t!\n249\t\n250\tClip #!\n251\tsummarize\n252\t\n253\tMovie Metadata\n254\tVLM\n255\t\n256\tScene Representation\n257\tMovie Context\n258\t\n259\tFace Tracklets\n260\t\n261\tReinforce\n262\tor Decay Saliency\n263\t\n264\tAssign or Update Identity\n265\t\n266\tdescribe\n267\t\n268\tSubject Action Object Context\n269\t\n270\t$\n271\t\n272\tc\n273\t\n274\t!\n275\t\n276\t\"\n277\t\n278\tCharacter\n279\tRepresentation\n280\t\n281\tCharacter ID\n282\t\n283\tFact\n284\t\n285\tSaliency Weight\n286\t\n287\tIdentity Graph \"!\n288\t\n289\tNarrative Memory ℳ!\n290\t\n291\tCandidate Facts\n292\tInsert\n293\t\n294\tACCEPT\n295\t\n296\tREJECT\n297\t\n298\tverify\n299\t\n300\tNarrative State !!\n301\t\n302\tFig. 2: Overview of StoryTeller. Before processing clip vt , the system maintains\n303\tthe narrative state St−1 = (Gt−1 , Mt−1 ), where Gt−1 is the identity graph and Mt−1\n304\tis the narrative memory. Given vt , StoryTeller (1) updates the identity graph to maintain character continuity, (2) extracts structured factual candidates using the updated\n305\tidentity graph, optional public movie metadata, and the previous narrative memory,\n306\tand (3) updates the narrative memory using semantic filtering, VLM verification, and\n307\treinforcement–decay salience dynamics. Public movie metadata may suggest character\n308\tnames or plot context, but only visually verified facts are stored in narrative memory.\n309\t\n310\tand supported by the video. Third, the salience-based narrative memory updates\n311\tthe importance of stored facts: facts that remain relevant are reinforced, while\n312\tfacts that no longer matter gradually decay. This allows important characters,\n313\tevents, and relationships to persist across scenes without carrying forward every\n314\ttransient detail.\n315\tBesides the visual clips, the movie title is used to retrieve optional public\n316\tmovie metadata. The retrieved metadata may suggest character names or plot\n317\tcontext, but it cannot by itself create a memory entry or directly influence the\n318\tgenerated narration. A fact is added to the narrative memory only if it is supported by the current clip and accepted by the semantic filtering and VLM\n319\tverification steps.\n320\t3.1\n321\t\n322\tIdentity Graph Update\n323\t\n324\tThe identity graph Gt−1 stores character representations accumulated from previously processed clips. Its role is to associate recurring appearances of the\n325\tsame person across clips, fostering consistent character references throughout\n326\tthe movie.\n327\tUnlike conventional character banks in the AD literature [10,38], which store\n328\tstatic character representations, our identity graph is updated continuously as\n329\tnew visual observations and verified narrative evidence become available. This\n330\tallows recurring characters to be tracked consistently across scenes, while novel\n331\tcharacter identities can be established progressively as sufficient supporting evidence accumulates.\n332\tTracklets and Embeddings. For each clip vt , faces are detected in each frame\n333\tand associated into short temporal tracklets Tk , where each tracklet represents a\n334\tsingle face observed over consecutive frames. A pretrained ArcFace encoder ϕ [3]\n335\textracts an embedding vt,i = ϕ(xt,i ) for each face crop xt,i . The embedding of\n336\t\n337\t\fStoryTeller\n338\t\n339\t7\n340\t\n341\ttracklet Tk is obtained by averaging the embeddings of all face observations in\n342\tthe tracklet:\n343\t  \\mathbf {e}_k = \\frac {1}{|\\mathcal {T}_k|} \\sum _{i\\in \\mathcal {T}_k} \\mathbf {v}_{t,i}. \n344\t\n345\t(3)\n346\t\n347\tIdentity Graph Representation. The identity graph at time t is defined as\n348\t  \\mathcal {G}_t = \\{(c_j, \\boldsymbol {\\mu }_j)\\}_{j=1}^{N_t}, \n349\t\n350\t(4)\n351\t\n352\twhere cj denotes a character identity and µj is the mean embedding of all\n353\ttracklets assigned to that character. The graph therefore maintains a compact\n354\trepresentation of characters observed up to time t.\n355\tIdentity Assignment. For each new tracklet embedding ek , we compute its\n356\tcosine similarity to every existing identity embedding:\n357\t  j^* = \\arg \\max _j \\cos (\\mathbf {e}_k,\\boldsymbol {\\mu }_j). \n358\t\n359\t(5)\n360\t\n361\tIf cos(ek , µj ∗ ) > τ , the tracklet is assigned to identity cj ∗ . Otherwise, a\n362\tnew identity node is created and the tracklet remains unnamed until sufficient\n363\tevidence is accumulated to associate it with a character.\n364\tIdentity Reseeding. Characters often appear before their names are revealed.\n365\tAccordingly, every face tracklet is initially represented as an anonymous identity. The VLM may consult optional public movie metadata when proposing a\n366\tcharacter name, but the current clip must provide sufficient visual and narrative\n367\tevidence before the association is accepted. Once verified, the corresponding\n368\tanonymous identity is assigned the character name, and the identity graph is\n369\tupdated by creating a new named node or updating an existing one. Previously\n370\tobserved or future tracklets that are visually similar can then be associated with\n371\tthe same identity. Thus, the similarity threshold τ serves only as a candidate\n372\tmatching criterion rather than proof of identity. Tracklets that lack sufficient visual or narrative evidence remain anonymous until additional evidence becomes\n373\tavailable.\n374\t3.2\n375\t\n376\tGrounded Fact Induction\n377\t\n378\tGiven the current clip vt , the updated identity graph Gt containing recurring\n379\tcharacter identities, and the narrative memory Mt−1 summarizing previously accumulated story information, StoryTeller then inducts facts, i.e., extracts structured factual candidates and filters them before they are inserted into memory.\n380\tThe objective is to identify facts that are both visually supported and consistent\n381\twith the evolving narrative context to achieve a new narrative memory Mt .\n382\tScene Representation. We first summarize the visual content of the clip. A\n383\tVLM generates a concise scene summary st describing the primary event in\n384\tvt . The summary is then embedded as st = ε(st ), where ε(·) denotes the text\n385\tembedding function.\n386\t\n387\t\f8\n388\t\n389\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n390\t\n391\tPublic Movie Metadata Retrieval. Before fact induction, StoryTeller uses\n392\tthe movie title to retrieve optional public movie metadata, including plot summaries, character lists, and short character descriptions from IMDb. Each paragraph is embedded, and the paragraphs most similar to the current scene summary st are retrieved. The retrieved metadata serves only as auxiliary context:\n393\tit may suggest character names or plot context, but it is never copied into the\n394\tnarration or directly stored in the narrative memory. All stored facts must be\n395\tsupported by the current clip and accepted by the semantic filtering and VLM\n396\tverification steps.\n397\tIf little or no metadata is available, retrieval simply returns fewer or no\n398\tpassages. The remainder of the pipeline is unchanged: facts are still extracted\n399\tand verified, the identity graph and narrative memory are updated from visual\n400\tevidence, and unnamed characters remain anonymous until sufficient evidence\n401\tsupports an identity assignment.\n402\tStructured Fact Extraction. Given clip vt , the VLM proposes structured\n403\tfactual candidates conditioned on three sources of context: (i) recurring character\n404\tidentities from the identity graph Gt , (ii) optional public movie metadata, and\n405\t(iii) relevant narrative context retrieved from the memory Mt−1 . Each candidate\n406\tis represented as\n407\t  f=(\\text {subject},\\text {action},\\text {object},\\text {context}), \n408\twhere the subject may correspond to either a named character or an anonymous identity. The extracted candidates describe potential narrative updates,\n409\tincluding character actions, interactions, object states, and scene context.\n410\tThis stage is intentionally permissive: it generates hypotheses rather than\n411\tcommitting facts to memory. Candidate facts, including proposed character\n412\tnames inferred from optional public movie metadata, are accepted only after\n413\tthe semantic filtering and VLM verification.\n414\tSemantic Filtering. The extracted candidates may include facts that are only\n415\tweakly related to the current clip or inconsistent with the evolving narrative. Before applying computationally expensive VLM verification, we use a lightweight\n416\tsemantic filter to retain candidates that are either semantically related to the\n417\tcurrent scene or consistent with previously verified facts.\n418\tEach candidate fact f is embedded as zf = ε(f ). We compute\n419\t  g_f = \\max \\left ( \\cos (\\mathbf {z}_f,\\mathbf {s}_t), \\max _m \\cos (\\mathbf {z}_f,\\varepsilon (f_m)) \\right ), \n420\t\n421\t(6)\n422\t\n423\twhere fm denotes the m-th fact stored in the narrative memory Mt−1 . The\n424\tfirst term measures semantic similarity to the current scene summary, while\n425\tthe second measures consistency with previously verified facts. Candidate facts\n426\twith gf > σ are forwarded to VLM verification. We use a conservative highrecall threshold for σ to discard only clearly unrelated candidates while retaining\n427\tplausible facts for subsequent verification.\n428\tVerification Stage. Candidates that pass semantic filtering are evaluated by\n429\ta dedicated VLM verifier using the current clip. The verifier outputs ACCEPT or\n430\tREJECT. Only accepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory or used to\n431\t\n432\t\fStoryTeller\n433\t\n434\t9\n435\t\n436\tupdate named identities. This stage prevents semantic consistency from being\n437\tmistaken for visual evidence: a candidate may agree with retrieved metadata or\n438\tpreviously verified memory, but it cannot update the identity graph or narrative\n439\tmemory unless the video supports it.\n440\t3.3\n441\t\n442\tSalience-Based Narrative Memory\n443\t\n444\tAfter verification, accepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory Mt .\n445\tEach memory entry consists of a validated fact and an associated salience weight\n446\tthat determines its influence on future narration.\n447\tFormally, the memory at time t is\n448\t  \\mathcal {M}_t = \\{ (f_m, w_m^{(t)}) \\}, \n449\t\n450\t(7)\n451\t\n452\t(t)\n453\t\n454\twhere fm is the m-th validated fact and wm is its salience weight at time t.\n455\tAccepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory with an initial salience\n456\t(0)\n457\tweight wm = 0.25.\n458\tRelevance Computation. For the current scene summary st , we compute\n459\tthe semantic similarity between the scene embedding st and each stored fact\n460\tembedding zm = ε(fm ):\n461\t  r_m^{(t)} = \\cos (\\mathbf {s}_t,\\mathbf {z}_m). \n462\t\n463\t(8)\n464\t\n465\t(t)\n466\tReinforcement–Decay Dynamics. The relevance score rm determines how\n467\t\n468\tstrongly fact fm should be reinforced. Memory weights evolve through reinforcement and decay: at each scene, every fact decays slightly, and facts relevant to\n469\tthe current scene are reinforced in proportion to their relevance:\n470\t  w_m^{(t)} = \\lambda \\, w_m^{(t-1)} + \\alpha \\, r_m^{(t)}, \\qquad \\lambda \\in (0,1). \n471\t\n472\t(9)\n473\t\n474\tHere λ is the decay factor, applied to the previous weight, and α is the reinforcement strength. A fact that stays relevant across scenes keeps gaining weight and\n475\t(t)\n476\tremains salient, while a fact that stops being relevant (rm = 0) loses a fixed\n477\tfraction of its weight each scene and gradually fades. Supplementary Sec. S5\n478\tvisualizes persistent and transient memory dynamics.\n479\t\n480\t4\n481\t\n482\tStoryAD-QA: Evaluating Narrative Comprehension\n483\t\n484\tExisting captioning metrics such as CIDEr [34], SPICE [1], ROUGE [21], and\n485\tBLEU [25] measure lexical or semantic similarity between generated and reference descriptions. While effective for evaluating caption quality at the scene level,\n486\tthey do not assess whether a sequence of audio descriptions preserves the information needed to understand a story. Narrative comprehension requires tracking\n487\tcharacters, relationships, events, and causal developments across scenes, yet ADs\n488\tare essentially concise and may omit important context. As a result, high captioning scores do not necessarily indicate strong story-level understanding. To\n489\t\n490\t\f10\n491\t\n492\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n493\t\n494\tFile: 3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/segment_0068.mp4\n495\t\n496\taddress this limitation, we introduce StoryAD-QA, a multiple-choice benchmark\n497\tthat evaluates whether generated audio descriptions retain sufficient information\n498\tVideo\n499\tfor downstream narrative reasoning. Rather than comparing generated descripsrc: /gpudata3/minh/MovieQA/30s/3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/seg\n500\tment_0068.mp4\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"206fc7a5-df8a-4bee-9d63-61742ae2bbd5","uuid":"86785e87-3998-44be-8f3c-b1e0f0a23bc1","timestamp":"2026-07-14T11:32:02.292Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_2607_11798.txt","content":"StoryTeller: Training-Free Narrative Grounding\nfor Long-Form Audio Description\nSeung Hyun Hahm, Minh T. Dinh, and SouYoung Jin\n\narXiv:2607.11798v1 [cs.CV] 13 Jul 2026\n\nDartmouth College, USA\n{Seung.Hyun.Hahm.GR,Minh.T.Dinh.GR,SouYoung.Jin}@dartmouth.edu\n\nAbstract. Long-form audio description (AD) requires more than describing visible actions: it must preserve characters, events, relationships,\nand story context across scenes so that blind and low-vision (BLV) audiences can follow a film. Modern video–language models (VLMs) are effective on short clips, but they often treat each moment independently, producing descriptions that miss who characters are, why events matter, and\nhow the current scene connects to earlier narrative context. We propose\nStoryTeller, a training-free framework for story-aware long-form AD. Instead of relying only on local visual cues, StoryTeller maintains a verified\nnarrative memory that carries forward story-relevant information across\nscenes, enabling later descriptions to remain coherent, grounded, and\ncontextually informative. Given only raw video and a movie title, StoryTeller can optionally retrieve public movie metadata to resolve names\nand story context, while accepting only facts that are supported by the\nvideo through semantic filtering and VLM verification. The method requires no subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, aligned captions, character\nbanks, precomputed face identities, or task-specific fine-tuning. To evaluate whether generated AD preserves narrative information, we introduce\nStoryAD-QA1 , a question-answering benchmark that tests whether a\nlanguage model can answer story-context questions using only the generated descriptions. Experiments on standard AD benchmarks and diverse\nlong-form videos show that StoryTeller consistently improves narrative\ncoherence, factual grounding, and story comprehension over strong baselines in automatic, QA-based, and human evaluations.\nKeywords: audio description · long-form video understanding ·\nretrieval-augmented generation · narrative grounding · accessibility\n\n1\n\nIntroduction\n\nAudio description (AD) enables blind and low-vision (BLV) audiences to access\nvisual media by narrating important visual information between dialogue and\nother sounds. Effective AD goes beyond describing objects or actions in the\ncurrent frame: it identifies who is present, explains what has just happened,\n1\n\nStoryAD-QA benchmark dataset and evaluation code:\nhttps://github.com/SEE-AI-Lab/ECCV2026_StoryTeller_StoryAD_QA\n\n\f2\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\nBaseline\nAD\n\nAlbus Dumbledore makes his wand move with a flick of his wrist\nwhile conversing with someone. Harry is hit by a teacher,\nwhile Ron and Hermione look on.\n\nPrevious scene\n\nAlastor Mad\nEye Moody\nA professor at\nHogwarts\n\nIdentity Graph\n\nSubject: boy\nAction: covers\nObject: hair\nLocation: a desk\n\nObserved Fact\n\nSubject: Mad Eye Moody\nAction: holds\nObject: a spider\nLocation: room with a chalkboard\n\nMemory\n\nStoryTeller Mad Eye Moody presents a spider to the class.\nAD\nA boy covers his head as a spider crawls on it.\n\nFig. 1: Story-level audio description requires narrative memory. Existing audio description (AD) systems typically generate descriptions using only local visual\ncontext or static character banks, which often fails to preserve long-range narrative\nrelationships. Our StoryTeller instead maintains a persistent narrative state consisting of an identity graph that tracks characters across scenes and a salience-weighted\nmemory that accumulates narrative facts over time. This enables consistent character\nreferences and long-range story reasoning across an entire film. The baseline example\nis the output of AutoAD-Zero.\n\nconveys why a moment matters, and connects the scene to the broader narrative.\nProfessional AD writers are able to provide this narrative grounding because\nthey watch the film and write with the whole story in mind. However, producing\nhigh-quality AD remains costly and time-intensive, and copyright restrictions\nmake large publicly distributable AD datasets difficult to obtain.\nRecent advances in video–language models (VLMs) [2,19,30,36] and large language models have motivated research on automatic AD generation. State-of-theart identity-aware AD systems [8,9,27] are typically trained as task-specific models on curated movie datasets such as LSMDC [28] and MAD [31]. These pipelines\nincorporate identity-aware components built from face-recognition backbones\ntrained on labeled data. While effective in benchmark settings, this reliance on\ncopyrighted training data, curated movie annotations, and specialized identity\nmodules limits their scalability, reproducibility, and applicability to new films.\nTraining-free pipelines, including AutoAD-Zero [38] and MM_Narrator [40],\nhave recently emerged as an alternative to supervised AD generation. These\nmethods remove the need for task-specific model training, but they often still\nrely on resources prepared before AD generation, including character banks,\naligned subtitles, or existing AD transcripts. Moreover, they typically propagate\ncontext in shallow or static forms, such as concatenating previous descriptions\nor reusing fixed identity features. Although these strategies can improve local\nconsistency across nearby clips, they do not explicitly model how narrative in-\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n3\n\nformation evolves over time: which characters, relationships, and events should\nremain salient, and which details should fade as the film progresses.\nHuman viewers do not understand a film by retaining a complete list of previous frames. Instead, they maintain an evolving representation of the story,\nwhere central characters, unresolved conflicts, and recurring relationships remain salient, while incidental visual details gradually lose importance. This perspective suggests that long-form AD should preserve identity continuity, causal\nstructure, and evolving character interactions across a film, without relying on\nexternal resources such as subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, character banks, or\nprecomputed face identities.\nWe introduce StoryTeller, a training-free framework for long-form AD that\nmaintains an explicit story state as it processes clips in chronological order. Given\na sequence of video clips {v1 , . . . , vT }, the system keeps two forms of memory:\nan identity graph for recurring characters and a salience-weighted memory for\nverified story facts. Each new clip updates this state through three steps: track\nvisible identities, extract candidate facts with optional public movie metadata,\nand verify those facts against the video before updating memory. The memory\nthen reinforces facts that remain relevant and decays facts that no longer matter.\nStoryTeller takes as input only the raw video and a movie title. The title\nmay be used to retrieve public IMDb plot summaries, character lists, and short\ncharacter descriptions. This retrieved text is only a source of possible names or\ncontext; it is not copied into the AD, stored directly as memory, or treated as\nground truth. A fact enters memory only if it is supported by the current clip\nand accepted by semantic filtering and VLM verification.\nBeyond generation, we also address evaluation. Standard metrics such as\nBLEU [25], CIDEr [34], and SPICE [1] measure lexical overlap between generated\ndescriptions and reference captions, but they do not evaluate whether a listener\ncan reconstruct the narrative from the AD alone. To address this limitation, we\nintroduce StoryAD-QA, a narrative-comprehension question-answering benchmark. For each scene, we generate questions whose answers depend on both\nthe current clip and preceding narrative context. During evaluation, a language\nmodel receives only the generated audio descriptions and must answer these\nquestions without access to the video. This protocol directly measures whether\nthe description preserves characters, events, and causal relationships necessary\nfor story understanding rather than merely describing visual details in isolation.\nContributions.\n– We propose StoryTeller, a fully training-free framework for long-form audio\ndescription that uses raw video and public title-keyed metadata without\nsubtitles, AD transcripts, manually curated visual character banks, or taskspecific fine-tuning.\n– We introduce an explicit narrative memory mechanism with reinforcement–\ndecay dynamics that approximates how human viewers track evolving story\nsalience across scenes.\n\n\f4\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\n– We present StoryAD-QA, a narrative-comprehension QA benchmark that\nevaluates whether generated audio descriptions support story understanding\nbeyond lexical similarity.\n\n2\n\nRelated Work\n\nBenchmarking Audio Description Generation. Movie understanding has\noften been studied as question answering over long videos [13, 32, 33, 35, 39].\nFor example, MovieQA [33] uses questions grounded in plot summaries, scripts,\nand subtitles, while [35] and [13] annotate characters, interactions, and story\nstructure. MovieChat [32] emphasizes on long-video QA with sparse memory\nand introduces MovieChat-1K. These datasets are crucial for evaluating video\nreasoning, but they do not directly ask whether an AD gives a listener enough\ninformation to understand the story without seeing the video.\nDatasets designed specifically for AD instead focus on localized narration.\nLSMDC [28] and MAD [31] provide large-scale movie captioning resources\naligned to short clips, and recent AD generation systems [8–10, 26, 27, 38, 40]\nbuild on these datasets with identity-aware modules or curated character banks.\nDespite their usefulness, evaluation in these works often relies on direct string\ncomparison with professional AD using metrics such as CIDEr [34], SPICE [1],\nand ROUGE [21], which are highly sensitive to temporal alignment. Addressing\nthis limitation, AutoAD II [8] introduces an evaluation protocol that measures\nwhether generated descriptions are semantically aligned with nearby groundtruth annotations rather than requiring exact sentence matches. Building on this\ndirection, AutoAD III [10] further proposes CRITIC for evaluating character\nretrieval and LLM-AD-Eval for sentence-level semantic scoring with LLMs.\nMore recently, question-answering evaluation has been explored to assess\nthe usefulness of AD. ADQA [15] evaluates whether generated AD supports\nvisual appreciation and narrative understanding in a certain video segment via\nquestions generated from reference descriptions. Instead, our benchmark focuses\non long-form narrative grounding, evaluating whether ADs preserve information\nrequired for reasoning over story context that spans multiple scenes.\nIdentity Modeling in Video Narratives. Maintaining consistent character\nidentity across scenes is essential for long-form video understanding and AD. Several recent AD systems explicitly rely on character banks–precomputed repositories of character-specific visual features, e.g., face embeddings or reference images\nused to recognize recurring characters throughout a movie [8–10]. In contrast,\nStoryTeller requires no character bank or precomputed face identities. Instead, it\ndiscovers recurring identities directly from repeated face observations, allowing\ncharacter identities to emerge dynamically as narrative evidence accumulates.\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation. Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)\nimproves grounding by incorporating external evidence during generation [5,\n18]. However, naive retrieval can introduce irrelevant or contradictory information and may amplify hallucinations in multimodal models [12, 29]. Prior\nwork improves retrieval quality through dense retrievers and structured fusion\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n5\n\nmechanisms [7, 14, 16], but these approaches focus primarily on factual knowledge grounding rather than narrative coherence. Our approach instead performs\nnarrative-aware retrieval restricted to movie-scoped sources and triggered only\nwhen scene observations indicate potentially story-relevant events.\nMemory for Long-Horizon Reasoning. Memory mechanisms have been\nwidely explored for long-horizon multimodal reasoning. Recent systems such\nas VideoAgent [4], Optimus-1 [20], and M3-Agent [23] maintain explicit temporal memories to support extended video reasoning. Other long-video systems\nemploy episodic memories for VideoQA [37], retrieval-augmented memories for\nlong-video comprehension [24], or global audio-visual character representations\nfor dense video description [11]. These methods primarily target long-video QA,\nembodied reasoning, video comprehension, or dense video description. In contrast, StoryTeller is designed for accessibility-oriented audio description, where\ngenerated descriptions are intended to complement the original movie audio\nrather than summarize the entire film. Instead of maintaining a general-purpose\nmemory, StoryTeller stores a lightweight narrative memory of visually verified\nstory facts with evolving salience weights, allowing important characters and\nevents to persist across scenes while transient details gradually fade.\n\n3\n\nStoryTeller\n\nFigure 2 illustrates the overall pipeline of StoryTeller. The input is a movie\ndivided into chronological clips {v1 , . . . , vT }. StoryTeller processes the clips sequentially while carrying a persistent narrative state that summarizes story information accumulated from previously processed clips. This state enables the\nsystem to track recurring characters, extract scene-level events, and preserve\nlong-range narrative context throughout the movie.\nBefore processing clip vt , the system maintains the narrative state\n  \\mathcal {S}_{t-1} = (\\mathcal {G}_{t-1}, \\mathcal {M}_{t-1}), \n\n(1)\n\nwhere Gt−1 is the identity graph storing visual representations of recurring\ncharacters, and Mt−1 is the narrative memory storing verified story facts together with their salience weights.\nProcessing clip vt updates the narrative state according to\n  \\mathcal {S}_{t} = \\Phi (v_t, \\mathcal {S}_{t-1}), \n\n(2)\n\nwhere Φ denotes the overall state update operator.\nFor each new clip, StoryTeller updates its narrative state through three modules. First, the identity graph update links visible faces to existing character\nnodes when there is sufficient visual evidence, allowing the system to maintain\nconsistent references to recurring characters across clips. Second, grounded fact\ninduction proposes structured facts about the current scene, optionally using\npublic movie metadata as hints for names or story context. These candidate\nfacts are then filtered to ensure that they are semantically relevant to the scene\n\n\f6\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\nMovie-Scoped\nRetrieval\n\n!\n\nClip #!\nsummarize\n\nMovie Metadata\nVLM\n\nScene Representation\nMovie Context\n\nFace Tracklets\n\nReinforce\nor Decay Saliency\n\nAssign or Update Identity\n\ndescribe\n\nSubject Action Object Context\n\n$\n\nc\n\n!\n\n\"\n\nCharacter\nRepresentation\n\nCharacter ID\n\nFact\n\nSaliency Weight\n\nIdentity Graph \"!\n\nNarrative Memory ℳ!\n\nCandidate Facts\nInsert\n\nACCEPT\n\nREJECT\n\nverify\n\nNarrative State !!\n\nFig. 2: Overview of StoryTeller. Before processing clip vt , the system maintains\nthe narrative state St−1 = (Gt−1 , Mt−1 ), where Gt−1 is the identity graph and Mt−1\nis the narrative memory. Given vt , StoryTeller (1) updates the identity graph to maintain character continuity, (2) extracts structured factual candidates using the updated\nidentity graph, optional public movie metadata, and the previous narrative memory,\nand (3) updates the narrative memory using semantic filtering, VLM verification, and\nreinforcement–decay salience dynamics. Public movie metadata may suggest character\nnames or plot context, but only visually verified facts are stored in narrative memory.\n\nand supported by the video. Third, the salience-based narrative memory updates\nthe importance of stored facts: facts that remain relevant are reinforced, while\nfacts that no longer matter gradually decay. This allows important characters,\nevents, and relationships to persist across scenes without carrying forward every\ntransient detail.\nBesides the visual clips, the movie title is used to retrieve optional public\nmovie metadata. The retrieved metadata may suggest character names or plot\ncontext, but it cannot by itself create a memory entry or directly influence the\ngenerated narration. A fact is added to the narrative memory only if it is supported by the current clip and accepted by the semantic filtering and VLM\nverification steps.\n3.1\n\nIdentity Graph Update\n\nThe identity graph Gt−1 stores character representations accumulated from previously processed clips. Its role is to associate recurring appearances of the\nsame person across clips, fostering consistent character references throughout\nthe movie.\nUnlike conventional character banks in the AD literature [10,38], which store\nstatic character representations, our identity graph is updated continuously as\nnew visual observations and verified narrative evidence become available. This\nallows recurring characters to be tracked consistently across scenes, while novel\ncharacter identities can be established progressively as sufficient supporting evidence accumulates.\nTracklets and Embeddings. For each clip vt , faces are detected in each frame\nand associated into short temporal tracklets Tk , where each tracklet represents a\nsingle face observed over consecutive frames. A pretrained ArcFace encoder ϕ [3]\nextracts an embedding vt,i = ϕ(xt,i ) for each face crop xt,i . The embedding of\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n7\n\ntracklet Tk is obtained by averaging the embeddings of all face observations in\nthe tracklet:\n  \\mathbf {e}_k = \\frac {1}{|\\mathcal {T}_k|} \\sum _{i\\in \\mathcal {T}_k} \\mathbf {v}_{t,i}. \n\n(3)\n\nIdentity Graph Representation. The identity graph at time t is defined as\n  \\mathcal {G}_t = \\{(c_j, \\boldsymbol {\\mu }_j)\\}_{j=1}^{N_t}, \n\n(4)\n\nwhere cj denotes a character identity and µj is the mean embedding of all\ntracklets assigned to that character. The graph therefore maintains a compact\nrepresentation of characters observed up to time t.\nIdentity Assignment. For each new tracklet embedding ek , we compute its\ncosine similarity to every existing identity embedding:\n  j^* = \\arg \\max _j \\cos (\\mathbf {e}_k,\\boldsymbol {\\mu }_j). \n\n(5)\n\nIf cos(ek , µj ∗ ) > τ , the tracklet is assigned to identity cj ∗ . Otherwise, a\nnew identity node is created and the tracklet remains unnamed until sufficient\nevidence is accumulated to associate it with a character.\nIdentity Reseeding. Characters often appear before their names are revealed.\nAccordingly, every face tracklet is initially represented as an anonymous identity. The VLM may consult optional public movie metadata when proposing a\ncharacter name, but the current clip must provide sufficient visual and narrative\nevidence before the association is accepted. Once verified, the corresponding\nanonymous identity is assigned the character name, and the identity graph is\nupdated by creating a new named node or updating an existing one. Previously\nobserved or future tracklets that are visually similar can then be associated with\nthe same identity. Thus, the similarity threshold τ serves only as a candidate\nmatching criterion rather than proof of identity. Tracklets that lack sufficient visual or narrative evidence remain anonymous until additional evidence becomes\navailable.\n3.2\n\nGrounded Fact Induction\n\nGiven the current clip vt , the updated identity graph Gt containing recurring\ncharacter identities, and the narrative memory Mt−1 summarizing previously accumulated story information, StoryTeller then inducts facts, i.e., extracts structured factual candidates and filters them before they are inserted into memory.\nThe objective is to identify facts that are both visually supported and consistent\nwith the evolving narrative context to achieve a new narrative memory Mt .\nScene Representation. We first summarize the visual content of the clip. A\nVLM generates a concise scene summary st describing the primary event in\nvt . The summary is then embedded as st = ε(st ), where ε(·) denotes the text\nembedding function.\n\n\f8\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nPublic Movie Metadata Retrieval. Before fact induction, StoryTeller uses\nthe movie title to retrieve optional public movie metadata, including plot summaries, character lists, and short character descriptions from IMDb. Each paragraph is embedded, and the paragraphs most similar to the current scene summary st are retrieved. The retrieved metadata serves only as auxiliary context:\nit may suggest character names or plot context, but it is never copied into the\nnarration or directly stored in the narrative memory. All stored facts must be\nsupported by the current clip and accepted by the semantic filtering and VLM\nverification steps.\nIf little or no metadata is available, retrieval simply returns fewer or no\npassages. The remainder of the pipeline is unchanged: facts are still extracted\nand verified, the identity graph and narrative memory are updated from visual\nevidence, and unnamed characters remain anonymous until sufficient evidence\nsupports an identity assignment.\nStructured Fact Extraction. Given clip vt , the VLM proposes structured\nfactual candidates conditioned on three sources of context: (i) recurring character\nidentities from the identity graph Gt , (ii) optional public movie metadata, and\n(iii) relevant narrative context retrieved from the memory Mt−1 . Each candidate\nis represented as\n  f=(\\text {subject},\\text {action},\\text {object},\\text {context}), \nwhere the subject may correspond to either a named character or an anonymous identity. The extracted candidates describe potential narrative updates,\nincluding character actions, interactions, object states, and scene context.\nThis stage is intentionally permissive: it generates hypotheses rather than\ncommitting facts to memory. Candidate facts, including proposed character\nnames inferred from optional public movie metadata, are accepted only after\nthe semantic filtering and VLM verification.\nSemantic Filtering. The extracted candidates may include facts that are only\nweakly related to the current clip or inconsistent with the evolving narrative. Before applying computationally expensive VLM verification, we use a lightweight\nsemantic filter to retain candidates that are either semantically related to the\ncurrent scene or consistent with previously verified facts.\nEach candidate fact f is embedded as zf = ε(f ). We compute\n  g_f = \\max \\left ( \\cos (\\mathbf {z}_f,\\mathbf {s}_t), \\max _m \\cos (\\mathbf {z}_f,\\varepsilon (f_m)) \\right ), \n\n(6)\n\nwhere fm denotes the m-th fact stored in the narrative memory Mt−1 . The\nfirst term measures semantic similarity to the current scene summary, while\nthe second measures consistency with previously verified facts. Candidate facts\nwith gf > σ are forwarded to VLM verification. We use a conservative highrecall threshold for σ to discard only clearly unrelated candidates while retaining\nplausible facts for subsequent verification.\nVerification Stage. Candidates that pass semantic filtering are evaluated by\na dedicated VLM verifier using the current clip. The verifier outputs ACCEPT or\nREJECT. Only accepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory or used to\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n9\n\nupdate named identities. This stage prevents semantic consistency from being\nmistaken for visual evidence: a candidate may agree with retrieved metadata or\npreviously verified memory, but it cannot update the identity graph or narrative\nmemory unless the video supports it.\n3.3\n\nSalience-Based Narrative Memory\n\nAfter verification, accepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory Mt .\nEach memory entry consists of a validated fact and an associated salience weight\nthat determines its influence on future narration.\nFormally, the memory at time t is\n  \\mathcal {M}_t = \\{ (f_m, w_m^{(t)}) \\}, \n\n(7)\n\n(t)\n\nwhere fm is the m-th validated fact and wm is its salience weight at time t.\nAccepted facts are inserted into the narrative memory with an initial salience\n(0)\nweight wm = 0.25.\nRelevance Computation. For the current scene summary st , we compute\nthe semantic similarity between the scene embedding st and each stored fact\nembedding zm = ε(fm ):\n  r_m^{(t)} = \\cos (\\mathbf {s}_t,\\mathbf {z}_m). \n\n(8)\n\n(t)\nReinforcement–Decay Dynamics. The relevance score rm determines how\n\nstrongly fact fm should be reinforced. Memory weights evolve through reinforcement and decay: at each scene, every fact decays slightly, and facts relevant to\nthe current scene are reinforced in proportion to their relevance:\n  w_m^{(t)} = \\lambda \\, w_m^{(t-1)} + \\alpha \\, r_m^{(t)}, \\qquad \\lambda \\in (0,1). \n\n(9)\n\nHere λ is the decay factor, applied to the previous weight, and α is the reinforcement strength. A fact that stays relevant across scenes keeps gaining weight and\n(t)\nremains salient, while a fact that stops being relevant (rm = 0) loses a fixed\nfraction of its weight each scene and gradually fades. Supplementary Sec. S5\nvisualizes persistent and transient memory dynamics.\n\n4\n\nStoryAD-QA: Evaluating Narrative Comprehension\n\nExisting captioning metrics such as CIDEr [34], SPICE [1], ROUGE [21], and\nBLEU [25] measure lexical or semantic similarity between generated and reference descriptions. While effective for evaluating caption quality at the scene level,\nthey do not assess whether a sequence of audio descriptions preserves the information needed to understand a story. Narrative comprehension requires tracking\ncharacters, relationships, events, and causal developments across scenes, yet ADs\nare essentially concise and may omit important context. As a result, high captioning scores do not necessarily indicate strong story-level understanding. To\n\n\f10\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nFile: 3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/segment_0068.mp4\n\naddress this limitation, we introduce StoryAD-QA, a multiple-choice benchmark\nthat evaluates whether generated audio descriptions retain sufficient information\nVideo\nfor downstream narrative reasoning. Rather than comparing generated descripsrc: /gpudata3/minh/MovieQA/30s/3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/seg\nment_0068.mp4","numLines":500,"startLine":1,"totalLines":2339}}}
