{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-91b1b4d09eb384e9","type":"tool_result","content":"500\tment_0068.mp4\n501\ttions against Video\n502\treference text, StoryAD-QA measures whether questions about the\n503\t/gpudata3/minh/MovieQA/60s/3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/\n504\tstory can be src:\n505\tanswered\n506\tusing only the generated AD.\n507\tIndex: 61/74\n508\t\n509\tsegment_0031.mp4\n510\t\n511\tContext Video\n512\t\n513\tTrack B\n514\t\n515\tTrack A\n516\t\n517\tman_1\n518\t\n519\tMain Video\n520\t\n521\tman_2\n522\t\n523\tAfter the man in glasses stops to light a cigarette outside a building, what happens when he\n524\tapproaches the black SUV parked on the street?\n525\tA. He gets into the driver's seat and drives away.\n526\tD. A police officer exits the vehicle and asks for his identification.\n527\tB. The rear window rolls down to reveal a man sitting inside. E. He uses the car's side mirror to adjust his glasses.\n528\tC. He places a package on the hood of the vehicle.\n529\t\n530\tAfter leaving the building where he was seen receiving a haircut, what does the man do while\n531\tstanding on the sidewalk?\n532\tA. He hails a passing black vehicle.\n533\tB. He checks the time on his wristwatch.\n534\tC. He lights and smokes a cigarette.\n535\t\n536\tD. He makes a phone call on a mobile device.\n537\tE. He adjusts his tie while looking in a window.\n538\t\n539\tFig. 3: Example of questions from two tracks in StoryAD-QA. Grey panels\n540\tshow frames from the preceding context window used in Track B for question generation. The context reveals that the man was receiving a haircut inside the building,\n541\tenabling the question to reference this earlier event. Blue panels show the main clip,\n542\tIn the target scene, the man (who was identified in the context as receiving a haircut) is seen walking out onto\n543\twhere the man standsRationale:\n544\toutside\n545\tthe\n546\tand\n547\tlights\n548\ta cigarette,\n549\tthe sidewalk,\n550\twhere he\n551\tpulls abuilding\n552\tcigarette pack from\n553\this pocket,\n554\tlights a cigarette,\n555\tand stands there which\n556\tsmoking it. determines\n557\tthe correct answer. During evaluation, only the AD of the main clip is provided, so the\n558\tdescription must preserve or reintroduce the earlier context.\n559\t\n560\t4.1\n561\t\n562\tBenchmark Construction\n563\t\n564\tStoryAD-QA is constructed from movie clips derived from the MAD-Eval [31]\n565\tdataset. In total, the benchmark contains 2,574 questions across two evaluation tracks: 1,611 in Track A (segment-only QA) and 963 in Track B (contextconditioned QA). See Supplementary Table S6 for additional dataset statistics.\n566\tEach example in StoryAD-QA consists of a video segment and, following\n567\tprior work [15, 17], a multiple-choice question with five answer options, exactly\n568\tone of which is correct. Questions are generated automatically using a visionlanguage model (VLM) that observes the original video along with short movielevel metadata describing the overall story context. The VLM is instructed to\n569\tfocus on clearly observable events or outcomes and to avoid relying on dialogue,\n570\texternal knowledge, or subjective interpretation. This ensures that answers are\n571\tgrounded in visual evidence rather than speculation. All answer choices are randomly shuffled before evaluation to reduce positional bias. During evaluation,\n572\tthe answering model receives only the AD text for the evaluated segment and\n573\tthe answer choices; it receives no video, retrieved IMDb/Wikipedia metadata,\n574\tmovie title, or dialogue transcript.\n575\t\n576\t\fStoryTeller\n577\t\n578\t4.2\n579\t\n580\t11\n581\t\n582\tEvaluation Protocol\n583\t\n584\tTo evaluate whether generated AD preserves narrative information beyond individual frames, StoryAD-QA uses multiple-choice question answering over continuous movie segments. Questions are generated from video segments, but during\n585\tevaluation an answerer (a Language Model) receives only the generated AD\n586\ttext, together with the question and answer choices, without access to the original video. Accuracy is the fraction of questions answered correctly from the AD\n587\ttext alone. We report two complementary evaluation tracks (See Table 3).\n588\tTrack A: Segment-only QA. In Track A, questions are generated from a single\n589\tcontinuous video segment of 30, 60, 120, or 240 seconds. During evaluation, the\n590\tanswering model receives the generated ADs for that same segment and selects\n591\tthe correct option. This track asks whether the AD captures the key events,\n592\tentities, and relationships within the observed segment.\n593\tTrack B: Context-conditioned QA. In Track B, each question is constructed\n594\tfrom a fixed 30-second main clip together with its preceding context. The question generator observes the main clip plus c ∈ 30, 60, 90 seconds of video immediately before it. During evaluation, however, the answerer receives only the\n595\tAD generated for the 30-second main clip, along with the question and answer\n596\tchoices; it does not receive the preceding context or the original video. This\n597\tsetting tests whether the main-clip AD preserves or reintroduces contextual information from earlier scenes, such as character identities, ongoing actions, and\n598\tnarrative relationships.\n599\tAll questions retained in StoryAD-QA are manually verified before inclusion.\n600\tHuman annotators check that each question is visually grounded, has plausible\n601\tdistractors, and has a correct answer. Low-quality questions are regenerated and\n602\tre-verified. Additional details are provided in Supplementary Sections S8.2–S8.3.\n603\t\n604\t5\n605\t\n606\tExperiments\n607\t\n608\tWe evaluate StoryTeller along three dimensions: (i) captioning quality on MADEval, (ii) narrative comprehension with the proposed StoryAD-QA benchmark,\n609\tand (iii) the contribution of individual pipeline components through ablation\n610\tstudies. All experiments are conducted without task-specific training, subtitles,\n611\tscripts, AD transcripts, character banks, or precomputed face identities.\n612\t5.1\n613\t\n614\tExperimental Setup\n615\t\n616\tDatasets. We evaluate our method on MAD-Eval [31], which consists of 10\n617\tmovies from the LSMDC [28] dataset. LSMDC contains 202 movies paired with\n618\tprofessionally authored audio descriptions aligned to the corresponding video\n619\tclips. To evaluate long-range narrative understanding, we further introduce and\n620\tevaluate on StoryAD-QA, a question-answering benchmark constructed from\n621\tnon-overlapping segments of the MAD-Eval movies.\n622\tImplementation Details. We use Qwen3-VL-2B-Instruct [19] for scene summarization and structured fact extraction. We use Qwen3-VL-8B-Thinking for\n623\t\n624\t\f12\n625\t\n626\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n627\t\n628\tfact verification, which outputs an ACCEPT/REJECT decision for each candidate fact. Text embeddings are computed with Qwen3-VL-Embedding-2B [19],\n629\tand face embeddings are extracted with ArcFace [3]. Gemini3-Flash [6] is used\n630\tonly for StoryAD-QA question generation and answering. For question generation, Gemini3-Flash receives the video and a short Wikipedia overview. For\n631\tanswering, it receives only the AD text, question, and answer choices. IMDb retrieval is used only by the AD-generation pipeline and is defined in Section 3.2.\n632\tAdditional implementation details are provided in Supplementary Sec. S4, and\n633\tthe full prompts are provided in Supplementary Sec. S10.\n634\tThreshold Calibration. Identity assignment uses a fixed cosine similarity\n635\tthreshold of τ = 0.58 for ArcFace embeddings. The semantic grounding threshold\n636\tis set to σ = 0.20, calibrated from grounding-score statistics collected on separate\n637\tcalibration runs to provide a high-recall semantic filter that removes only clearly\n638\tunrelated candidates before VLM verification. Both thresholds are fixed across\n639\tall experiments and are not tuned on the evaluation data. Additional calibration\n640\tstatistics and threshold analyses are provided in Supplementary Sec. S4.2.\n641\tRuntime. On one A100-SXM4-80GB GPU, StoryTeller processes a featurelength movie in approximately 3–4 hours. The semantic filter is approximately\n642\t3,000× faster than VLM verification, substantially reducing unnecessary verifier\n643\tcalls.\n644\tMemory Parameters. Narrative memory uses the reinforcement–decay mechanism described in Sec.3.3. All hyperparameters are fixed across experiments;\n645\tcomplete values are provided in Supplementary Table S4.3.\n646\t5.2\n647\t\n648\tMAD-Eval Benchmark Comparison\n649\t\n650\tTable 1 compares StoryTeller with prior audio description systems while separating required resources from captioning performance. We additionally evaluate a\n651\tvariant without public movie metadata retrieval in the ablation study (Table 2).\n652\tWe additionally evaluate StoryTeller on MovieChat [32] using 9 videos and\n653\t27 questions. Results are reported in Supplementary Sec. S7.\n654\t5.3\n655\t\n656\tAblation Study\n657\t\n658\tTo evaluate the contribution of each component in StoryTeller, we construct\n659\tcontrolled ablation variants on MAD-Eval (Table 2). Each variant removes one\n660\tmodule while keeping the remaining pipeline unchanged. All experiments use the\n661\tQwen3-VL backbone to isolate the contribution of the proposed components.\n662\tA1 (VLM-only narration). Direct VLM narration without structured fact\n663\textraction, identity tracking, verification, or narrative memory.\n664\tA2 (No schema). Replaces structured facts with scene summaries while preserving the sequential pipeline.\n665\tA3 (No memory). Removes cross-clip narrative memory while retaining perclip fact extraction and verification.\n666\tA4 (No identity). Removes persistent identity tracking, leaving facts in generic\n667\tform without consistent character grounding.\n668\t\n669\t\fStoryTeller\n670\t\n671\t13\n672\t\n673\tTable 1: Comparison on MAD-Eval. Train denotes whether task-specific training\n674\tis required. Curated Res. includes subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, aligned captions,\n675\tcharacter banks, or precomputed face identities. Public Meta. means public movie text\n676\tretrieved by title, such as IMDb plot summaries, character lists, and short character descriptions. VLM indicates the underlying vision-language model used by each method.\n677\tOur method requires neither additional training nor curated or precomputed movie\n678\tresources; the default setting uses public movie metadata.\n679\tMethod Setup\n680\tModel\n681\t\n682\tMetrics\n683\t\n684\tTrain\n685\t\n686\tCurated Res.\n687\t\n688\tPublic Meta.\n689\t\n690\tVLM\n691\t\n692\tCIDEr\n693\t\n694\tSPICE\n695\t\n696\tROUGE-L\n697\t\n698\tAutoAD-I [9]\n699\tAutoAD-II [8]\n700\tAutoAD-III [10]\n701\t\n702\t✓\n703\t✓\n704\t✓\n705\t\n706\t✓\n707\t✓\n708\t✓\n709\t\n710\t×\n711\t×\n712\t×\n713\t\n714\t-\n715\t\n716\t14.3\n717\t19.2\n718\t24.0\n719\t\n720\t4.4\n721\t-\n722\t\n723\t11.9\n724\t13.4\n725\t-\n726\t\n727\tMM-Vid [22]\n728\tMM-Narrator [40]\n729\tAutoAD-Zero [38]\n730\t\n731\t×\n732\t×\n733\t×\n734\t\n735\t✓\n736\t✓\n737\t✓\n738\t\n739\t✓\n740\t✓\n741\t✓\n742\t\n743\tGPT-4V\n744\tGPT 4\n745\tVideoLLaMA2\n746\t\n747\t6.1\n748\t13.9\n749\t22.4\n750\t\n751\t6.1\n752\t5.2\n753\t7.3\n754\t\n755\t9.8\n756\t13.4\n757\t14.4\n758\t\n759\tStoryTeller\n760\tStoryTeller\n761\t\n762\t×\n763\t×\n764\t\n765\t×\n766\t×\n767\t\n768\t✓\n769\t✓\n770\t\n771\tVideoLLaMA2\n772\tQwen3-VL\n773\t\n774\t19.1\n775\t21.4\n776\t\n777\t9.0\n778\t6.7\n779\t\n780\t16.0\n781\t15.3\n782\t\n783\tTable 2: Ablation results on MAD-Eval. A1–A4 remove one internal module while\n784\tkeeping the remaining modules unchanged. A5 disables public IMDb metadata only;\n785\tidentity, schema, and memory remain active.\n786\tVariant\n787\t\n788\tPublic Meta. Identity Schema Memory CIDEr SPICE ROUGE-L\n789\t\n790\tStoryTeller (Full)\n791\t\n792\t✓\n793\t\n794\t✓\n795\t\n796\t✓\n797\t\n798\t✓\n799\t\n800\t21.4\n801\t\n802\t6.7\n803\t\n804\t15.3\n805\t\n806\tA1 (VLM only)\n807\tA2 (No schema)\n808\tA3 (No memory)\n809\tA4 (No identity)\n810\tA5 (No IMDb)\n811\t\n812\t×\n813\t✓\n814\t✓\n815\t✓\n816\t×\n817\t\n818\t×\n819\t✓\n820\t✓\n821\t×\n822\t✓\n823\t\n824\t×\n825\t×\n826\t✓\n827\t✓\n828\t✓\n829\t\n830\t×\n831\t✓\n832\t×\n833\t✓\n834\t✓\n835\t\n836\t11.4\n837\t15.4\n838\t18.0\n839\t17.9\n840\t17.2\n841\t\n842\t4.3\n843\t4.4\n844\t6.0\n845\t5.6\n846\t4.8\n847\t\n848\t9.6\n849\t12.5\n850\t13.2\n851\t12.3\n852\t12.2\n853\t\n854\tA5 (No IMDb metadata). Disables public movie metadata retrieval while\n855\tretaining identity tracking, structured facts, verification, and narrative memory.\n856\tTable 2 shows that each proposed component contributes to StoryTeller,\n857\twith every ablation lowering MAD-Eval scores. Removing identity grounding\n858\t(A4) leads to relative drops of 16.4% in CIDEr, 16.4% in SPICE, and 19.6% in\n859\tROUGE-L, even though public movie metadata remains available. This suggests\n860\tthat external metadata alone is insufficient for maintaining narrative consistency,\n861\tand that persistent character resolution provides complementary information for\n862\tcoherent storytelling. A5 further isolates IMDb metadata: disabling it lowers\n863\tCIDEr/SPICE/ROUGE-L by 19.6%/28.4%/20.3%, showing that public metadata helps but is not the sole driver of performance.\n864\t5.4\n865\t\n866\tStoryAD-QA Narrative Evaluation\n867\t\n868\tTable 3 reports results on the StoryAD-QA benchmark. In Track A, which\n869\tevaluates understanding within a single video segment, StoryTeller consistently\n870\toutperforms AutoAD-Zero across all segment lengths. The gains remain clear\n871\t\n872\t\f14\n873\t\n874\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n875\t\n876\tTable 3: StoryAD-QA QA benchmark (Accuracy). (a) Segment-only QA. (b)\n877\tContext-conditioned QA with c seconds of prior context plus a 30 s main clip; only the\n878\t30 s main-clip ADs are provided during evaluation. Reference AD denotes professional\n879\thuman-written AD text.\n880\t(a) Track A: Segment-only QA\n881\t\n882\tModel\n883\t\n884\t30\n885\t\n886\t60\n887\t\n888\t120\n889\t\n890\t(b) Track B: Context-conditioned QA\n891\t\n892\t240\n893\t\n894\tModel\n895\t\n896\t30+30 60+30 90+30\n897\t\n898\tReference AD 0.953 0.963 0.995 0.981\n899\t\n900\tReference AD 0.828 0.825 0.806\n901\t\n902\tAutoAD-Zero 0.840 0.830 0.896 0.917\n903\tStoryTeller 0.892 0.928 0.953 0.972\n904\t\n905\tAutoAD-Zero 0.662 0.654 0.673\n906\tStoryTeller 0.754 0.716 0.788\n907\t\n908\tfor longer segments, suggesting that narrative-aware descriptions better capture\n909\tstory-level information beyond local clip content.\n910\tTrack B evaluates contextual reasoning by generating questions using preceding context while providing only the ADs of the 30-second main clip during evaluation. Across all settings, StoryTeller achieves higher accuracy than AutoADZero, with the largest improvement of +11.5 points in the 90+30 setting. These\n911\tresults indicate that the generated narration more effectively preserves contextual cues such as character identities and ongoing events, enabling the answering\n912\tmodel to recover information originating from earlier clips.\n913\tThe “Reference AD” row uses the professional AD text supplied with MADEval as the answerer’s input. Because professional AD is scene-limited and may\n914\tomit details needed for some generated questions, its accuracy is not necessarily\n915\t100%.\n916\tTable 4 presents component ablations on StoryAD-QA. Several simplified\n917\tvariants remain competitive on short or local settings, but the complete system achieves the best performance on the longest and most context-dependent\n918\tsettings: 240s in Track A and 90+30 in Track B. Removing narrative memory\n919\t(A3), the identity graph (A4), or IMDb metadata (A5) reduces performance in\n920\tthese long-range settings, highlighting the role of each component. Notably, even\n921\twithout IMDb metadata, A5 remains competitive with or above AutoAD-Zero\n922\tacross all settings, indicating that the gains are not solely attributable to public\n923\tmovie information.\n924\t5.5\n925\t\n926\tQualitative Results\n927\t\n928\tFigure 4 compares professional reference AD, AutoAD-Zero, and StoryTeller, illustrating differences in identity consistency and narrative recall across clips.\n929\tAdditional qualitative examples are provided in Supplementary Fig. S1 and\n930\tSecs. S2–S3; human evaluation and preference results are reported in Sec. S9.\n931\t\n932\t6\n933\t\n934\tConclusion\n935\t\n936\tWe introduced StoryTeller, a training-free framework for long-form audio description that uses narrative memory to capture evolving story context across\n937\t\n938\t\fStoryTeller\n939\t\n940\t15\n941\t\n942\tTable 4: Component ablations on StoryAD-QA accuracy. A1: VLM only; A2: no\n943\tstructured schema; A3: no narrative memory; A4: no identity graph; A5: no IMDb\n944\tmetadata.\n945\tTrack A\n946\t\n947\tTrack B\n948\t\n949\tVariant\n950\t\n951\t30s\n952\t\n953\t60s\n954\t\n955\t120s\n956\t\n957\t240s\n958\t\n959\t30+30\n960\t\n961\t60+30\n962\t\n963\t90+30\n964\t\n965\tFull\n966\tA1\n967\tA2\n968\tA3\n969\tA4\n970\tA5\n971\t\n972\t0.892\n973\t0.908\n974\t0.905\n975\t0.899\n976\t0.909\n977\t0.892\n978\t\n979\t0.928\n980\t0.904\n981\t0.909\n982\t0.907\n983\t0.904\n984\t0.909\n985\t\n986\t0.953\n987\t0.928\n988\t0.932\n989\t0.918\n990\t0.908\n991\t0.908\n992\t\n993\t0.972\n994\t0.911\n995\t0.931\n996\t0.891\n997\t0.921\n998\t0.901\n999\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"206fc7a5-df8a-4bee-9d63-61742ae2bbd5","uuid":"9cc4845e-96d2-4a5f-8379-36d9c19a8180","timestamp":"2026-07-14T11:32:17.717Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_2607_11798.txt","content":"ment_0068.mp4\ntions against Video\nreference text, StoryAD-QA measures whether questions about the\n/gpudata3/minh/MovieQA/60s/3034_IDES_OF_MARCH/\nstory can be src:\nanswered\nusing only the generated AD.\nIndex: 61/74\n\nsegment_0031.mp4\n\nContext Video\n\nTrack B\n\nTrack A\n\nman_1\n\nMain Video\n\nman_2\n\nAfter the man in glasses stops to light a cigarette outside a building, what happens when he\napproaches the black SUV parked on the street?\nA. He gets into the driver's seat and drives away.\nD. A police officer exits the vehicle and asks for his identification.\nB. The rear window rolls down to reveal a man sitting inside. E. He uses the car's side mirror to adjust his glasses.\nC. He places a package on the hood of the vehicle.\n\nAfter leaving the building where he was seen receiving a haircut, what does the man do while\nstanding on the sidewalk?\nA. He hails a passing black vehicle.\nB. He checks the time on his wristwatch.\nC. He lights and smokes a cigarette.\n\nD. He makes a phone call on a mobile device.\nE. He adjusts his tie while looking in a window.\n\nFig. 3: Example of questions from two tracks in StoryAD-QA. Grey panels\nshow frames from the preceding context window used in Track B for question generation. The context reveals that the man was receiving a haircut inside the building,\nenabling the question to reference this earlier event. Blue panels show the main clip,\nIn the target scene, the man (who was identified in the context as receiving a haircut) is seen walking out onto\nwhere the man standsRationale:\noutside\nthe\nand\nlights\na cigarette,\nthe sidewalk,\nwhere he\npulls abuilding\ncigarette pack from\nhis pocket,\nlights a cigarette,\nand stands there which\nsmoking it. determines\nthe correct answer. During evaluation, only the AD of the main clip is provided, so the\ndescription must preserve or reintroduce the earlier context.\n\n4.1\n\nBenchmark Construction\n\nStoryAD-QA is constructed from movie clips derived from the MAD-Eval [31]\ndataset. In total, the benchmark contains 2,574 questions across two evaluation tracks: 1,611 in Track A (segment-only QA) and 963 in Track B (contextconditioned QA). See Supplementary Table S6 for additional dataset statistics.\nEach example in StoryAD-QA consists of a video segment and, following\nprior work [15, 17], a multiple-choice question with five answer options, exactly\none of which is correct. Questions are generated automatically using a visionlanguage model (VLM) that observes the original video along with short movielevel metadata describing the overall story context. The VLM is instructed to\nfocus on clearly observable events or outcomes and to avoid relying on dialogue,\nexternal knowledge, or subjective interpretation. This ensures that answers are\ngrounded in visual evidence rather than speculation. All answer choices are randomly shuffled before evaluation to reduce positional bias. During evaluation,\nthe answering model receives only the AD text for the evaluated segment and\nthe answer choices; it receives no video, retrieved IMDb/Wikipedia metadata,\nmovie title, or dialogue transcript.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n4.2\n\n11\n\nEvaluation Protocol\n\nTo evaluate whether generated AD preserves narrative information beyond individual frames, StoryAD-QA uses multiple-choice question answering over continuous movie segments. Questions are generated from video segments, but during\nevaluation an answerer (a Language Model) receives only the generated AD\ntext, together with the question and answer choices, without access to the original video. Accuracy is the fraction of questions answered correctly from the AD\ntext alone. We report two complementary evaluation tracks (See Table 3).\nTrack A: Segment-only QA. In Track A, questions are generated from a single\ncontinuous video segment of 30, 60, 120, or 240 seconds. During evaluation, the\nanswering model receives the generated ADs for that same segment and selects\nthe correct option. This track asks whether the AD captures the key events,\nentities, and relationships within the observed segment.\nTrack B: Context-conditioned QA. In Track B, each question is constructed\nfrom a fixed 30-second main clip together with its preceding context. The question generator observes the main clip plus c ∈ 30, 60, 90 seconds of video immediately before it. During evaluation, however, the answerer receives only the\nAD generated for the 30-second main clip, along with the question and answer\nchoices; it does not receive the preceding context or the original video. This\nsetting tests whether the main-clip AD preserves or reintroduces contextual information from earlier scenes, such as character identities, ongoing actions, and\nnarrative relationships.\nAll questions retained in StoryAD-QA are manually verified before inclusion.\nHuman annotators check that each question is visually grounded, has plausible\ndistractors, and has a correct answer. Low-quality questions are regenerated and\nre-verified. Additional details are provided in Supplementary Sections S8.2–S8.3.\n\n5\n\nExperiments\n\nWe evaluate StoryTeller along three dimensions: (i) captioning quality on MADEval, (ii) narrative comprehension with the proposed StoryAD-QA benchmark,\nand (iii) the contribution of individual pipeline components through ablation\nstudies. All experiments are conducted without task-specific training, subtitles,\nscripts, AD transcripts, character banks, or precomputed face identities.\n5.1\n\nExperimental Setup\n\nDatasets. We evaluate our method on MAD-Eval [31], which consists of 10\nmovies from the LSMDC [28] dataset. LSMDC contains 202 movies paired with\nprofessionally authored audio descriptions aligned to the corresponding video\nclips. To evaluate long-range narrative understanding, we further introduce and\nevaluate on StoryAD-QA, a question-answering benchmark constructed from\nnon-overlapping segments of the MAD-Eval movies.\nImplementation Details. We use Qwen3-VL-2B-Instruct [19] for scene summarization and structured fact extraction. We use Qwen3-VL-8B-Thinking for\n\n\f12\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nfact verification, which outputs an ACCEPT/REJECT decision for each candidate fact. Text embeddings are computed with Qwen3-VL-Embedding-2B [19],\nand face embeddings are extracted with ArcFace [3]. Gemini3-Flash [6] is used\nonly for StoryAD-QA question generation and answering. For question generation, Gemini3-Flash receives the video and a short Wikipedia overview. For\nanswering, it receives only the AD text, question, and answer choices. IMDb retrieval is used only by the AD-generation pipeline and is defined in Section 3.2.\nAdditional implementation details are provided in Supplementary Sec. S4, and\nthe full prompts are provided in Supplementary Sec. S10.\nThreshold Calibration. Identity assignment uses a fixed cosine similarity\nthreshold of τ = 0.58 for ArcFace embeddings. The semantic grounding threshold\nis set to σ = 0.20, calibrated from grounding-score statistics collected on separate\ncalibration runs to provide a high-recall semantic filter that removes only clearly\nunrelated candidates before VLM verification. Both thresholds are fixed across\nall experiments and are not tuned on the evaluation data. Additional calibration\nstatistics and threshold analyses are provided in Supplementary Sec. S4.2.\nRuntime. On one A100-SXM4-80GB GPU, StoryTeller processes a featurelength movie in approximately 3–4 hours. The semantic filter is approximately\n3,000× faster than VLM verification, substantially reducing unnecessary verifier\ncalls.\nMemory Parameters. Narrative memory uses the reinforcement–decay mechanism described in Sec.3.3. All hyperparameters are fixed across experiments;\ncomplete values are provided in Supplementary Table S4.3.\n5.2\n\nMAD-Eval Benchmark Comparison\n\nTable 1 compares StoryTeller with prior audio description systems while separating required resources from captioning performance. We additionally evaluate a\nvariant without public movie metadata retrieval in the ablation study (Table 2).\nWe additionally evaluate StoryTeller on MovieChat [32] using 9 videos and\n27 questions. Results are reported in Supplementary Sec. S7.\n5.3\n\nAblation Study\n\nTo evaluate the contribution of each component in StoryTeller, we construct\ncontrolled ablation variants on MAD-Eval (Table 2). Each variant removes one\nmodule while keeping the remaining pipeline unchanged. All experiments use the\nQwen3-VL backbone to isolate the contribution of the proposed components.\nA1 (VLM-only narration). Direct VLM narration without structured fact\nextraction, identity tracking, verification, or narrative memory.\nA2 (No schema). Replaces structured facts with scene summaries while preserving the sequential pipeline.\nA3 (No memory). Removes cross-clip narrative memory while retaining perclip fact extraction and verification.\nA4 (No identity). Removes persistent identity tracking, leaving facts in generic\nform without consistent character grounding.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n13\n\nTable 1: Comparison on MAD-Eval. Train denotes whether task-specific training\nis required. Curated Res. includes subtitles, scripts, AD transcripts, aligned captions,\ncharacter banks, or precomputed face identities. Public Meta. means public movie text\nretrieved by title, such as IMDb plot summaries, character lists, and short character descriptions. VLM indicates the underlying vision-language model used by each method.\nOur method requires neither additional training nor curated or precomputed movie\nresources; the default setting uses public movie metadata.\nMethod Setup\nModel\n\nMetrics\n\nTrain\n\nCurated Res.\n\nPublic Meta.\n\nVLM\n\nCIDEr\n\nSPICE\n\nROUGE-L\n\nAutoAD-I [9]\nAutoAD-II [8]\nAutoAD-III [10]\n\n✓\n✓\n✓\n\n✓\n✓\n✓\n\n×\n×\n×\n\n-\n\n14.3\n19.2\n24.0\n\n4.4\n-\n\n11.9\n13.4\n-\n\nMM-Vid [22]\nMM-Narrator [40]\nAutoAD-Zero [38]\n\n×\n×\n×\n\n✓\n✓\n✓\n\n✓\n✓\n✓\n\nGPT-4V\nGPT 4\nVideoLLaMA2\n\n6.1\n13.9\n22.4\n\n6.1\n5.2\n7.3\n\n9.8\n13.4\n14.4\n\nStoryTeller\nStoryTeller\n\n×\n×\n\n×\n×\n\n✓\n✓\n\nVideoLLaMA2\nQwen3-VL\n\n19.1\n21.4\n\n9.0\n6.7\n\n16.0\n15.3\n\nTable 2: Ablation results on MAD-Eval. A1–A4 remove one internal module while\nkeeping the remaining modules unchanged. A5 disables public IMDb metadata only;\nidentity, schema, and memory remain active.\nVariant\n\nPublic Meta. Identity Schema Memory CIDEr SPICE ROUGE-L\n\nStoryTeller (Full)\n\n✓\n\n✓\n\n✓\n\n✓\n\n21.4\n\n6.7\n\n15.3\n\nA1 (VLM only)\nA2 (No schema)\nA3 (No memory)\nA4 (No identity)\nA5 (No IMDb)\n\n×\n✓\n✓\n✓\n×\n\n×\n✓\n✓\n×\n✓\n\n×\n×\n✓\n✓\n✓\n\n×\n✓\n×\n✓\n✓\n\n11.4\n15.4\n18.0\n17.9\n17.2\n\n4.3\n4.4\n6.0\n5.6\n4.8\n\n9.6\n12.5\n13.2\n12.3\n12.2\n\nA5 (No IMDb metadata). Disables public movie metadata retrieval while\nretaining identity tracking, structured facts, verification, and narrative memory.\nTable 2 shows that each proposed component contributes to StoryTeller,\nwith every ablation lowering MAD-Eval scores. Removing identity grounding\n(A4) leads to relative drops of 16.4% in CIDEr, 16.4% in SPICE, and 19.6% in\nROUGE-L, even though public movie metadata remains available. This suggests\nthat external metadata alone is insufficient for maintaining narrative consistency,\nand that persistent character resolution provides complementary information for\ncoherent storytelling. A5 further isolates IMDb metadata: disabling it lowers\nCIDEr/SPICE/ROUGE-L by 19.6%/28.4%/20.3%, showing that public metadata helps but is not the sole driver of performance.\n5.4\n\nStoryAD-QA Narrative Evaluation\n\nTable 3 reports results on the StoryAD-QA benchmark. In Track A, which\nevaluates understanding within a single video segment, StoryTeller consistently\noutperforms AutoAD-Zero across all segment lengths. The gains remain clear\n\n\f14\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nTable 3: StoryAD-QA QA benchmark (Accuracy). (a) Segment-only QA. (b)\nContext-conditioned QA with c seconds of prior context plus a 30 s main clip; only the\n30 s main-clip ADs are provided during evaluation. Reference AD denotes professional\nhuman-written AD text.\n(a) Track A: Segment-only QA\n\nModel\n\n30\n\n60\n\n120\n\n(b) Track B: Context-conditioned QA\n\n240\n\nModel\n\n30+30 60+30 90+30\n\nReference AD 0.953 0.963 0.995 0.981\n\nReference AD 0.828 0.825 0.806\n\nAutoAD-Zero 0.840 0.830 0.896 0.917\nStoryTeller 0.892 0.928 0.953 0.972\n\nAutoAD-Zero 0.662 0.654 0.673\nStoryTeller 0.754 0.716 0.788\n\nfor longer segments, suggesting that narrative-aware descriptions better capture\nstory-level information beyond local clip content.\nTrack B evaluates contextual reasoning by generating questions using preceding context while providing only the ADs of the 30-second main clip during evaluation. Across all settings, StoryTeller achieves higher accuracy than AutoADZero, with the largest improvement of +11.5 points in the 90+30 setting. These\nresults indicate that the generated narration more effectively preserves contextual cues such as character identities and ongoing events, enabling the answering\nmodel to recover information originating from earlier clips.\nThe “Reference AD” row uses the professional AD text supplied with MADEval as the answerer’s input. Because professional AD is scene-limited and may\nomit details needed for some generated questions, its accuracy is not necessarily\n100%.\nTable 4 presents component ablations on StoryAD-QA. Several simplified\nvariants remain competitive on short or local settings, but the complete system achieves the best performance on the longest and most context-dependent\nsettings: 240s in Track A and 90+30 in Track B. Removing narrative memory\n(A3), the identity graph (A4), or IMDb metadata (A5) reduces performance in\nthese long-range settings, highlighting the role of each component. Notably, even\nwithout IMDb metadata, A5 remains competitive with or above AutoAD-Zero\nacross all settings, indicating that the gains are not solely attributable to public\nmovie information.\n5.5\n\nQualitative Results\n\nFigure 4 compares professional reference AD, AutoAD-Zero, and StoryTeller, illustrating differences in identity consistency and narrative recall across clips.\nAdditional qualitative examples are provided in Supplementary Fig. S1 and\nSecs. S2–S3; human evaluation and preference results are reported in Sec. S9.\n\n6\n\nConclusion\n\nWe introduced StoryTeller, a training-free framework for long-form audio description that uses narrative memory to capture evolving story context across\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n15\n\nTable 4: Component ablations on StoryAD-QA accuracy. A1: VLM only; A2: no\nstructured schema; A3: no narrative memory; A4: no identity graph; A5: no IMDb\nmetadata.\nTrack A\n\nTrack B\n\nVariant\n\n30s\n\n60s\n\n120s\n\n240s\n\n30+30\n\n60+30\n\n90+30\n\nFull\nA1\nA2\nA3\nA4\nA5\n\n0.892\n0.908\n0.905\n0.899\n0.909\n0.892\n\n0.928\n0.904\n0.909\n0.907\n0.904\n0.909\n\n0.953\n0.928\n0.932\n0.918\n0.908\n0.908\n\n0.972\n0.911\n0.931\n0.891\n0.921\n0.901\n","numLines":500,"startLine":500,"totalLines":2339}}}
