Garcia, A.G.,\n1148\tBraunstein, A., Liu, A., Schmidt, A., Mereskin, A., Mishchenko, A., Applebaum,\n1149\tA., Rogerson, A., Rajan, A., Wei, A., Kotha, A., Srivastava, A., Agrawal, A., Vijayvergiya, A., Tyra, A., Nair, A., Nayak, A., Eggers, B., Ji, B., Hoover, B., Chen,\n1150\tB., Chen, B., Barak, B., Minaiev, B., Hao, B., Baker, B., Lightcap, B., McKinzie,\n1151\tB., Wang, B., Quinn, B., Fioca, B., Hsu, B., Yang, B., Yu, B., Zhang, B., Brenner,\n1152\tB., Zetino, C.R., Raymond, C., Lugaresi, C., Paz, C., Hudson, C., Whitney, C., Li,\n1153\tC., Chen, C., Cole, C., Voss, C., Ding, C., Shen, C., Huang, C., Colby, C., Hallacy,\n1154\tC., Koch, C., Lu, C., Kaplan, C., Kim, C., Minott-Henriques, C., Frey, C., Yu, C.,\n1155\tCzarnecki, C., Reid, C., Wei, C., Decareaux, C., Scheau, C., Zhang, C., Forbes, C.,\n1156\tTang, D., Goldberg, D., Roberts, D., Palmie, D., Kappler, D., Levine, D., Wright,\n1157\tD., Leo, D., Lin, D., Robinson, D., Grabb, D., Chen, D., Lim, D., Salama, D.,\n1158\tBhattacharjee, D., Tsipras, D., Li, D., Yu, D., Strouse, D., Williams, D., Hunn,\n1159\tD., Bayes, E., Arbus, E., Akyurek, E., Le, E.Y., Widmann, E., Yani, E., Proehl,\n1160\tE., Sert, E., Cheung, E., Schwartz, E., Han, E., Jiang, E., Mitchell, E., Sigler, E.,\n1161\tWallace, E., Ritter, E., Kavanaugh, E., Mays, E., Nikishin, E., Li, F., Such, F.P.,\n1162\tde Avila Belbute Peres, F., Raso, F., Bekerman, F., Tsimpourlas, F., Chantzis, F.,\n1163\tSong, F., Zhang, F., Raila, G., McGrath, G., Briggs, G., Yang, G., Parascandolo,\n1164\tG., Chabot, G., Kim, G., Zhao, G., Valiant, G., Leclerc, G., Salman, H., Wang,\n1165\tH., Sheng, H., Jiang, H., Wang, H., Jin, H., Sikchi, H., Schmidt, H., Aspegren,\n1166\tH., Chen, H., Qiu, H., Lightman, H., Covert, I., Kivlichan, I., Silber, I., Sohl, I.,\n1167\tHammoud, I., Clavera, I., Lan, I., Akkaya, I., Kostrikov, I., Kofman, I., Etinger, I.,\n1168\tSingal, I., Hehir, J., Huh, J., Pan, J., Wilczynski, J., Pachocki, J., Lee, J., Quinn,\n1169\tJ., Kiros, J., Kalra, J., Samaroo, J., Wang, J., Wolfe, J., Chen, J., Wang, J., Harb,\n1170\tJ., Han, J., Wang, J., Zhao, J., Chen, J., Yang, J., Tworek, J., Chand, J., Landon,\n1171\tJ., Liang, J., Lin, J., Liu, J., Wang, J., Tang, J., Yin, J., Jang, J., Morris, J., Flynn,\n1172\tJ., Ferstad, J., Heidecke, J., Fishbein, J., Hallman, J., Grant, J., Chien, J., Gordon,\n1173\tJ., Park, J., Liss, J., Kraaijeveld, J., Guay, J., Mo, J., Lawson, J., McGrath, J.,\n1174\tVendrow, J., Jiao, J., Lee, J., Steele, J., Wang, J., Mao, J., Chen, K., Hayashi, K.,\n1175\tXiao, K., Salahi, K., Wu, K., Sekhri, K., Sharma, K., Singhal, K., Li, K., Nguyen,\n1176\tK., Gu-Lemberg, K., King, K., Liu, K., Stone, K., Yu, K., Ying, K., Georgiev, K.,\n1177\tLim, K., Tirumala, K., Miller, K., Ahmad, L., Lv, L., Clare, L., Fauconnet, L.,\n1178\tItow, L., Yang, L., Romaniuk, L., Anise, L., Byron, L., Pathak, L., Maksin, L., Lo,\n1179\tL., Ho, L., Jing, L., Wu, L., Xiong, L., Mamitsuka, L., Yang, L., McCallum, L.,\n1180\tHeld, L., Bourgeois, L., Engstrom, L., Kuhn, L., Feuvrier, L., Zhang, L., Switzer,\n1181\tL., Kondraciuk, L., Kaiser, L., Joglekar, M., Singh, M., Shah, M., Stratta, M.,\n1182\tWilliams, M., Chen, M., Sun, M., Cayton, M., Li, M., Zhang, M., Aljubeh, M.,\n1183\t\n1184\t\fStoryTeller\n1185\t\n1186\t19\n1187\t\n1188\tNichols, M., Haines, M., Schwarzer, M., Gupta, M., Shah, M., Guan, M.Y., Huang,\n1189\tM., Dong, M., Wang, M., Glaese, M., Carroll, M., Lampe, M., Malek, M., Sharman, M., Zhang, M., Wang, M., Pokrass, M., Florian, M., Pavlov, M., Wang, M.,\n1190\tChen, M., Wang, M., Feng, M., Bavarian, M., Lin, M., Abdool, M., Rohaninejad,\n1191\tM., Soto, N., Staudacher, N., LaFontaine, N., Marwell, N., Liu, N., Preston, N.,\n1192\tTurley, N., Ansman, N., Blades, N., Pancha, N., Mikhaylin, N., Felix, N., Handa,\n1193\tN., Rai, N., Keskar, N., Brown, N., Nachum, O., Boiko, O., Murk, O., Watkins,\n1194\tO., Gleeson, O., Mishkin, P., Lesiewicz, P., Baltescu, P., Belov, P., Zhokhov, P.,\n1195\tPronin, P., Guo, P., Thacker, P., Liu, Q., Yuan, Q., Liu, Q., Dias, R., Puckett,\n1196\tR., Arora, R., Mullapudi, R.T., Gaon, R., Miyara, R., Song, R., Aggarwal, R.,\n1197\tMarsan, R., Yemiru, R., Xiong, R., Kshirsagar, R., Nuttall, R., Tsiupa, R., Eldan,\n1198\tR., Wang, R., James, R., Ziv, R., Shu, R., Nigmatullin, R., Jain, S., Talaie, S.,\n1199\tAltman, S., Arnesen, S., Toizer, S., Toyer, S., Miserendino, S., Agarwal, S., Yoo,\n1200\tS., Heon, S., Ethersmith, S., Grove, S., Taylor, S., Bubeck, S., Banesiu, S., Amdo,\n1201\tS., Zhao, S., Wu, S., Santurkar, S., Zhao, S., Chaudhuri, S.R., Krishnaswamy, S.,\n1202\tShuaiqi, Xia, Cheng, S., Anadkat, S., Fishman, S.P., Tobin, S., Fu, S., Jain, S.,\n1203\tMei, S., Egoian, S., Kim, S., Golden, S., Mah, S., Lin, S., Imm, S., Sharpe, S.,\n1204\tYadlowsky, S., Choudhry, S., Eum, S., Sanjeev, S., Khan, T., Stramer, T., Wang,\n1205\tT., Xin, T., Gogineni, T., Christianson, T., Sanders, T., Patwardhan, T., Degry,\n1206\tT., Shadwell, T., Fu, T., Gao, T., Garipov, T., Sriskandarajah, T., Sherbakov, T.,\n1207\tKorbak, T., Kaftan, T., Hiratsuka, T., Wang, T., Song, T., Zhao, T., Peterson, T.,\n1208\tKharitonov, V., Chernova, V., Kosaraju, V., Kuo, V., Pong, V., Verma, V., Petrov,\n1209\tV., Jiang, W., Zhang, W., Zhou, W., Xie, W., Zhan, W., McCabe, W., DePue, W.,\n1210\tEllsworth, W., Bain, W., Thompson, W., Chen, X., Qi, X., Xiang, X., Shi, X.,\n1211\tDubois, Y., Yu, Y., Khakbaz, Y., Wu, Y., Qian, Y., Lee, Y.T., Chen, Y., Zhang,\n1212\tY., Xiong, Y., Tian, Y., Cha, Y., Bai, Y., Yang, Y., Yuan, Y., Li, Y., Zhang, Y.,\n1213\tYang, Y., Jin, Y., Jiang, Y., Wang, Y., Wang, Y., Liu, Y., Stubenvoll, Z., Dou,\n1214\tZ., Wu, Z., Wang, Z.: Openai gpt-5 system card. arXiv preprint arXiv:2601.03267\n1215\t(2025)\n1216\t31. Soldan, M., Pardo, A., Alcázar, J.L., Caba, F., Zhao, C., Giancola, S., Ghanem,\n1217\tB.: Mad: A scalable dataset for language grounding in videos from movie audio\n1218\tdescriptions. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision\n1219\tand Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 5026–5035 (June 2022)\n1220\t32. Song, E., Chai, W., Wang, G., Zhang, Y., Zhou, H., Wu, F., Chi, H., Guo, X., Ye,\n1221\tT., Zhang, Y., Lu, Y., Hwang, J.N., Wang, G.: Moviechat: From dense token to\n1222\tsparse memory for long video understanding. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF\n1223\tConference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 18221–\n1224\t18232 (June 2024)\n1225\t33. Tapaswi, M., Zhu, Y., Stiefelhagen, R., Torralba, A., Urtasun, R., Fidler, S.:\n1226\tMovieqa: Understanding stories in movies through question-answering. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 4631–4640 (2016)\n1227\t34. Vedantam, R., Zitnick, C.L., Parikh, D.: CIDEr: Consensus-based image description evaluation. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision\n1228\tand Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 4566–4575 (2015)\n1229\t35. Vicol, P., Tapaswi, M., Castrejon, L., Fidler, S.: Moviegraphs: Towards understanding human-centric situations from videos. In: IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer\n1230\tVision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR) (2018). https://doi.org/10.1109/\n1231\tCVPR.2018.00895\n1232\t\n1233\t\f20\n1234\t\n1235\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1236\t\n1237\t36. Wang, W., Gao, Z., Gu, L., Pu, H., Cui, L., Wei, X., Liu, Z., Jing, L., Ye, S., Shao,\n1238\tJ., Wang, Z., Chen, Z., Zhang, H., Yang, G., Wang, H., Wei, Q., Yin, J., Li, W.,\n1239\tCui, E., Chen, G., Ding, Z., Tian, C., Wu, Z., Xie, J., Li, Z., Yang, B., Duan, Y.,\n1240\tWang, X., Hou, Z., Hao, H., Zhang, T., Li, S., Zhao, X., Duan, H., Deng, N., Fu,\n1241\tB., He, Y., Wang, Y., He, C., Shi, B., He, J., Xiong, Y., Lv, H., Wu, L., Shao,\n1242\tW., Zhang, K., Deng, H., Qi, B., Ge, J., Guo, Q., Zhang, W., Zhang, S., Cao, M.,\n1243\tLin, J., Tang, K., Gao, J., Huang, H., Gu, Y., Lyu, C., Tang, H., Wang, R., Lv,\n1244\tH., Ouyang, W., Wang, L., Dou, M., Zhu, X., Lu, T., Lin, D., Dai, J., Su, W.,\n1245\tZhou, B., Chen, K., Qiao, Y., Wang, W., Luo, G.: Internvl3. 5: Advancing opensource multimodal models in versatility, reasoning, and efficiency. arXiv preprint\n1246\tarXiv:2508.18265 (2025)\n1247\t37. Wang, Y., Zhang, L., Liu, J., Yan, J., Zhang, Z., Zheng, J., Ma, A., Ling, R.,\n1248\tYang, X., Wu, D., Chen, X., Li, X.: Video-em: Event-centric episodic memory for\n1249\tlong-form video understanding. arXiv preprint arXiv:2508.09486 (2025). https:\n1250\t//doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2508.09486\n1251\t38. Xie, J., Han, T., Bain, M., Nagrani, A., Varol, G., Xie, W., Zisserman, A.: AutoADZero: A training-free framework for zero-shot audio description. In: Proceedings of\n1252\tthe Asian Conference on Computer Vision (ACCV). pp. 2265–2281 (2024)\n1253\t39. Yue, Z., Zhang, Q., Hu, A., Zhang, L., Wang, Z., Jin, Q.: Movie101: A new movie\n1254\tunderstanding benchmark. In: Proceedings of the Association for Computational\n1255\tLinguistics (ACL). pp. 4669–4684 (2023)\n1256\t40. Zhang, C., Lin, K., Yang, Z., Wang, J., Li, L., Lin, C.C., Liu, Z., Wang, L.: Mmnarrator: Narrating long-form videos with multimodal in-context learning. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 13647–13657 (2024)\n1257\t\n1258\t\fStoryTeller: Training-Free Narrative Grounding\n1259\tfor Long-Form Audio Description\n1260\t–Supplementary Material–\n1261\tSeung Hyun Hahm, Minh T. Dinh, and SouYoung Jin\n1262\tDartmouth College\n1263\t\n1264\tS1\n1265\t\n1266\tOverview\n1267\t\n1268\tThis supplementary document provides additional details and experimental results supporting the main paper. In particular, we include:\n1269\t– Additional qualitative comparisons between StoryTeller, AutoAD-Zero, and\n1270\tprofessional reference AD.\n1271\t– Failure cases of baseline methods and discussion of how StoryTeller improves\n1272\tnarrative consistency.\n1273\t– Analysis of narrative memory dynamics, including visualization of memory\n1274\tweights over time.\n1275\t– A backbone comparison explaining how the VideoLLaMA2 and Qwen3-VL\n1276\tconfigurations differ across MAD-Eval and StoryAD-QA results.\n1277\t– Further details and validation of the StoryAD-QA benchmark.\n1278\t– Human evaluation of generated audio descriptions.\n1279\t– Implementation details and hyperparameters used in the proposed framework.\n1280\t– Full prompt templates used in the StoryTeller pipeline.\n1281\tThese materials aim to improve transparency and reproducibility of the proposed framework.\n1282\t\n1283\tS2\n1284\t\n1285\tAdditional Qualitative Results\n1286\t\n1287\tThis section supports the qualitative analysis in Section 5.5 of the main paper\n1288\tby providing more examples beyond the main-paper figure.\n1289\tFigure S1 presents additional qualitative comparisons between StoryTeller,\n1290\tAutoAD-Zero, and professional reference AD across four movies: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire, The Ides of March, Roommate, and Legion. Each\n1291\texample shows three representative frames together with the generated audio\n1292\tdescriptions.\n1293\tAcross these examples, StoryTeller generally produces descriptions that include more concrete scene context visible in the frames, while AutoAD-Zero\n1294\toften focuses on shorter action-oriented phrases or more generic descriptions.\n1295\tThe differences can be observed directly in the examples.\n1296\t\n1297\t\f2\n1298\t\n1299\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1300\t\n1301\tFig. S1: Additional qualitative comparisons between StoryTeller, AutoAD-Zero, and\n1302\tprofessional reference AD across four movies. StoryTeller captures broader narrative\n1303\tcontext and scene semantics, while AutoAD-Zero often focuses on isolated actions or\n1304\tproduces generic descriptions.\n1305\t\n1306\tIn Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire, the frames show Harry fighting with\n1307\tthe chained dragon. StoryTeller describes Harry leaping over a rocky cliff while\n1308\tbeing pursued by the dragon, capturing the spatial interaction between the character and the environment. AutoAD-Zero instead focuses on Harry casting a spell\n1309\twith his wand. Both descriptions refer to the same moment, but they emphasize\n1310\tdifferent aspects of the scene.\n1311\tThe example from The Ides of March illustrates a scene with visible campaign\n1312\tsignage and buildings in the background. StoryTeller describes the police vehicle\n1313\tand the political signs visible in the frames. In contrast, AutoAD-Zero produces\n1314\ta more generic description about officers walking toward a building, which does\n1315\tnot explicitly mention the visual text present in the scene.\n1316\tIn the Roommate example, the first frame shows a character lying in bed,\n1317\tfollowed by outdoor campus scenes. StoryTeller describes both the indoor and\n1318\toutdoor settings shown across the frames. AutoAD-Zero produces a shorter description focused mainly on the sleeping character and nearby people walking.\n1319\tFinally, the Legion example shows a car driving along a desert road while a\n1320\tdust storm forms in the distance. StoryTeller describes the car moving toward the\n1321\tstorm and also mentions a small insect visible on the car vent in the final frame.\n1322\tAutoAD-Zero instead produces a more general description of the car driving and\n1323\ta person looking toward a dust cloud.\n1324\tThese examples highlight how the generated descriptions differ in content\n1325\temphasis across methods. StoryTeller tends to include environmental details\n1326\tvisible in the frames, while AutoAD-Zero often produces shorter descriptions\n1327\tcentered on basic actions.\n1328\t\n1329\t\fStoryTeller\n1330\t\n1331\tS3\n1332\t\n1333\t3\n1334\t\n1335\tComparative Error Analysis\n1336\t\n1337\tFig. S2: Qualitative comparison of audio descriptions. Examples comparing\n1338\tStoryTeller, AutoAD-Zero, and professional reference AD across several movies. Text\n1339\thighlighted in blue corresponds to information that is visually grounded in the frames\n1340\tand appears in both StoryTeller and the professional reference AD. Text highlighted\n1341\tin red marks content that is less consistent with the visual evidence in the scene.\n1342\tThese examples illustrate common challenges in automatic audio description, including\n1343\tgrounding textual cues, interpreting scene entities, and maintaining character identity\n1344\tacross scenes.\n1345\t\n1346\tFigure S2 presents representative qualitative examples comparing StoryTeller, AutoAD-Zero [4], and professional reference AD across several movies.\n1347\tThese examples highlight common challenges in automatic audio description,\n1348\tincluding difficulties in grounding textual cues, identifying scene entities, and\n1349\tmaintaining character identity across scenes.\n1350\tIn the figure, text highlighted in blue corresponds to information that is consistent with the visual frames and appears in both StoryTeller and the professional reference AD. Text highlighted in red marks content that is less consistent\n1351\twith the visual evidence in the scene.\n1352\tMissing textual or symbolic cues. In the The Ides of March example, the\n1353\tframe clearly shows a note containing the message “Meet me in the stairwell at\n1354\tnoon.” StoryTeller and the professional reference AD both capture this textual\n1355\tinformation, while the baseline description instead focuses on a generic action\n1356\t(“He walks”), overlooking the written content visible in the scene.\n1357\tObject grounding ambiguity. In the Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire\n1358\texample, the scene shows a figure approaching through fog behind the tents.\n1359\tStoryTeller and the professional reference AD describe the approaching figure,\n1360\twhereas the baseline description refers to a “red circle,” which does not clearly\n1361\tcorrespond to any object visible in the scene.\n1362\tScene interpretation differences. The Battle: Los Angeles example illustrates a case where the baseline description interprets the television display as\n1363\tpeople interacting with computer screens. In contrast, StoryTeller and the professional reference AD identify the meteor shower shown on the display.\n1364\tCharacter identity ambiguity. In the final example, the scene shows a character writing a note. StoryTeller correctly identifies the character as Jason and\n1365\tdescribes the action accordingly, while the baseline description refers to the character as “she,” which loses the identity information present in the narrative context.\n1366\t\n1367\t\f4\n1368\t\n1369\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1370\t\n1371\tThese examples highlight common challenges in grounding audio descriptions to visual evidence and maintaining narrative consistency across scenes. By\n1372\tincorporating structured narrative facts and an evolving memory mechanism,\n1373\tStoryTeller is able to produce descriptions that better preserve scene context\n1374\tand character identity.\n1375\t\n1376\tS4\n1377\t\n1378\tImplementation Details\n1379\t\n1380\tS4.1\n1381\t\n1382\tModel Configuration\n1383\t\n1384\tWe use the following models in the StoryTeller pipeline:\n1385\t– VLM for scene summarization and fact extraction: Qwen3-VL-2BInstruct\n1386\t– VLM for fact verification: Qwen3-VL-8B-Thinking\n1387\t– Text embedding model: Qwen3-VL-Embedding-2B\n1388\t– VLM for StoryAD-QA generation and answering: Gemini3-Flash for\n1389\tinitial question generation and answering; Gemini 3.5 Flash is used only to\n1390\tregenerate questions that fail the first manual verification pass.\n1391\t– Face recognition encoder: ArcFace [1]\n1392\tWithin each reported configuration, the same generation backbone is used\n1393\tconsistently unless a table explicitly compares backbones. Scene-level observations are first summarized into structured facts, which are then verified and\n1394\tstored in the narrative memory. During generation, StoryTeller retrieves the\n1395\tmost relevant verified facts and identity-consistent context to produce the final audio description. The AD pipeline may also retrieve IMDb plot summaries,\n1396\tcharacter lists, and short character descriptions using the movie title. These texts\n1397\tcan suggest possible names or plot context, but are not copied into narration or\n1398\ttreated as professional reference AD; accepted facts must be supported by the\n1399\tclip.\n1400\tExcept for Gemini, all models are executed locally on a cluster comprising\n1401\t8 NVIDIA A100-SXM4-80GB GPUs and 8 NVIDIA RTX 6000 Ada Generation\n1402\tGPUs. On one allocated A100-SXM4-80GB GPU, generating audio descriptions\n1403\tfor a single film requires approximately 3–4 hours, corresponding to roughly\n1404\t650 clips per movie. Across the 10 full movie runs, the pipeline processes 6,520\n1405\tclips and 13,974 candidate facts; verification takes 3.68 ± 1.73 seconds per fact\n1406\tblock, uses 473K tokens in total, and accepts 94.7% of candidate facts. The coarse\n1407\tsemantic gate is approximately 3,000× faster than VLM verification. Generating\n1408\tStoryAD-QA questions for the 10-movie evaluation set takes approximately 10–\n1409\t15 minutes per track.\n1410\tIn practice, generating the complete StoryAD-QA benchmark (2,574 questions across 10 movies) incurs an API cost of under $20, while evaluating the\n1411\tcomplete benchmark costs less than $5. These values are approximate and may\n1412\tvary depending on API pricing and the model’s internal reasoning-token usage.\n1413\t\n1414\t\fStoryTeller\n1415\t\n1416\t5\n1417\t\n1418\tTable S1: Hyperparameters used in StoryTeller.\n1419\tParameter\n1420\tValue\n1421\tIdentity threshold τ\n1422\t0.58\n1423\tGrounding threshold σ\n1424\t0.20\n1425\tReinforcement strength α 0.35\n1426\tDecay factor λ\n1427\t0.92\n1428\t(0)\n1429\tInitial memory weight wm 0.25\n1430\tTable S2: Effect of different semantic grounding thresholds. “Verifier calls saved” is\n1431\tmeasured relative to σ = 0.20.\n1432\tσ\n1433\t\n1434\tCalls saved\n1435\t\n1436\tAccepted facts\n1437\t\n1438\t0.20\n1439\t0.40\n1440\t0.45\n1441\t0.50\n1442\t0.55\n1443\t\n1444\t0.0%\n1445\t1.4%\n1446\t6.1%\n1447\t19.3%\n1448\t43.2%\n1449\t\n1450\t100.0%\n1451\t98.7%\n1452\t94.3%\n1453\t81.6%\n1454\t57.9%\n1455\t\n1456\tFor StoryAD-QA question generation only, Gemini3-Flash receives the video\n1457\tand a short Wikipedia movie overview. During question answering, it receives\n1458\tonly the generated AD text, question, and answer choices—never the source\n1459\tvideo, movie title, IMDb or Wikipedia text, subtitles, or other retrieved text.\n1460\t\n1461\tS4.2\n1462\t\n1463\tHyperparameters\n1464\t\n1465\tTable S1 summarizes the hyperparameters used in StoryTeller. These values\n1466\tare fixed globally across all experiments and are not tuned on the evaluation\n1467\tdatasets.\n1468\tGrounding Threshold (σ). The semantic grounding threshold determines\n1469\twhich candidate facts are forwarded to the computationally expensive VLM\n1470\tverification stage. To calibrate this threshold, we executed the complete StoryTeller pipeline on a separate set of movies and recorded the grounding score of\n1471\tevery extracted candidate fact, producing approximately 2,700 candidate facts.\n1472\tAmong candidate facts ultimately accepted by the verifier, the minimum\n1473\tobserved similarity was approximately 0.21, the 5th percentile was 0.36, and the\n1474\tmedian was 0.55. Based on these statistics, we selected σ = 0.20, slightly below\n1475\tthe minimum observed similarity, so that the semantic filter functions as a highrecall gate. Its purpose is not to decide factual correctness, but to remove clearly\n1476\tunrelated candidates before VLM verification.\n1477\tTable S2 reports the trade-off between computational cost and recall under\n1478\talternative threshold values. Higher thresholds reduce the number of verifier calls\n1479\tbut also discard visually supported facts. We therefore adopt the conservative\n1480\tsetting σ = 0.20 to prioritize narrative recall over computational savings.\n1481\t\n1482\t\f6\n1483\t\n1484\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1485\t\n1486\tTable S3: Hyperparameter robustness on the test split. Performance remains stable under moderate variation. StoryAD-QA results are reported as accuracy (%) for\n1487\tTrack A. The best performance for each metric is bolded.\n1488\tSetting\n1489\t\n1490\tCIDEr\n1491\t\n1492\tStoryAD-QA Accuracy (%)\n1493\t30s\n1494\t\n1495\t60s\n1496\t\n1497\t120s\n1498\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"206fc7a5-df8a-4bee-9d63-61742ae2bbd5","uuid":"0b770403-089b-426d-8630-4d2c49c80900","timestamp":"2026-07-14T11:38:35.976Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_2607_11798.txt","content":"\n0.754\n0.747\n0.796\n0.756\n0.794\n0.761\n\n0.716\n0.750\n0.709\n0.712\n0.750\n0.716\n\n0.788\n0.751\n0.751\n0.779\n0.774\n0.770\n\nFig. 4: Qualitative comparison of StoryTeller, AutoAD-Zero [38], and professional\nreference AD. (GT).\n\nscenes. By maintaining an identity graph and structured narrative memory, the\nsystem generates coherent descriptions without task-specific training or curated\nmovie resources; public movie metadata can suggest context, but only videosupported facts enter memory. We also introduced StoryAD-QA, a benchmark\nfor evaluating whether generated AD supports narrative understanding. Experiments show that narrative-aware modeling improves contextual grounding and\nstory comprehension in long-form video description.\n\nAcknowledgments\nThis work was supported by startup funds provided by Dartmouth College. The\nauthors also acknowledge support from the National Science Foundati