{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-b501796d0a4450d0","type":"tool_result","content":"1498\t\n1499\t240s\n1500\t\n1501\tDefault\n1502\t\n1503\t21.4\n1504\t\n1505\t89.2\n1506\t\n1507\t92.8\n1508\t\n1509\t95.3\n1510\t\n1511\t97.2\n1512\t\n1513\tα -20%\n1514\tα +20%\n1515\t\n1516\t20.2\n1517\t21.0\n1518\t\n1519\t89.4\n1520\t90.5\n1521\t\n1522\t94.4\n1523\t94.4\n1524\t\n1525\t96.2\n1526\t97.2\n1527\t\n1528\t97.2\n1529\t98.2\n1530\t\n1531\tλ -5%\n1532\tλ +5%\n1533\t\n1534\t21.9\n1535\t21.8\n1536\t\n1537\t89.7\n1538\t90.1\n1539\t\n1540\t94.2\n1541\t94.0\n1542\t\n1543\t95.3\n1544\t94.8\n1545\t\n1546\t97.2\n1547\t96.3\n1548\t\n1549\tIdentity Threshold (τ ). Identity assignment uses a fixed cosine similarity\n1550\tthreshold of τ = 0.58 for ArcFace embeddings. This value was selected empirically to balance missed associations and incorrect identity merges, and is kept\n1551\tfixed across all experiments.\n1552\tHyperparameter Robustness. Although StoryTeller introduces several global\n1553\thyperparameters (identity threshold τ , grounding threshold σ, reinforcement\n1554\tstrength α, and decay rate λ), these are fixed once and not tuned on evaluation\n1555\tdata. To assess robustness, we vary α within ±20% and λ within ±5% while\n1556\tkeeping the remaining parameters fixed. Performance on the test split remains\n1557\tstable, with StoryAD-QA accuracy varying by less than 3 percentage points and\n1558\tCIDEr by less than 6 percentage points. Results are summarized in Table S3.\n1559\tS4.3\n1560\t\n1561\tMemory Overhead of Identity Reseeding\n1562\t\n1563\tIdentity reseeding maintains a small backlog of unresolved (anonymous) tracklets until sufficient evidence is available for identity assignment. Each unresolved tracklet stores a single 512-dimensional ArcFace embedding (approximately 2 KB). Across all movies in our experiments, retaining this anonymous\n1564\tbacklog required less than 3.5 MB per movie, indicating that delayed identity\n1565\tassignment introduces negligible memory overhead.\n1566\tS4.4\n1567\t\n1568\tLimitations and Discussion\n1569\t\n1570\tStoryTeller maintains consistent character references using the identity graph\n1571\tdescribed in Section 3.1 of the main paper which associates face tracklets across\n1572\tclips through clustering and similarity-based assignment. In rare cases, clustering\n1573\terrors may temporarily associate a tracklet with the wrong identity. When this\n1574\toccurs, the generated description may mention an incorrect character name for\n1575\tthe corresponding scene.\n1576\tBecause StoryTeller maintains a persistent narrative state, such errors can\n1577\toften be corrected when stronger visual or narrative evidence becomes available.\n1578\t\n1579\t\fStoryTeller\n1580\t\n1581\t7\n1582\t\n1583\tIn particular, the reseeding mechanism described in Section 3.1 of the main\n1584\tpaper allows identities to be updated once additional observations clarify the\n1585\tcharacter assignment. However, if incorrect associations persist across several\n1586\tclips, the resulting descriptions may temporarily reduce narrative accuracy.\n1587\tInterestingly, this behavior also highlights the importance of maintaining an\n1588\texplicit narrative memory rather than relying solely on frame-level captioning.\n1589\tBy storing and updating structured narrative facts over time, the system can\n1590\trevise earlier assumptions and maintain consistent story context as additional\n1591\tevidence appears. Future work may further improve robustness by integrating\n1592\tstronger identity verification or multimodal reasoning mechanisms.\n1593\t\n1594\tS5\n1595\t\n1596\tAnalysis of Narrative Memory Dynamics\n1597\t\n1598\tTo better understand how StoryTeller maintains narrative context across long\n1599\tvideo sequences, we analyze the evolution of memory weights associated with\n1600\tverified narrative facts. Each fact fm stored in the narrative memory is associated\n1601\t(t)\n1602\twith a salience weight wm that reflects its current narrative importance. When\n1603\tlater scenes provide visual or semantic evidence supporting fm , the memory\n1604\t(t)\n1605\tmodule reinforces its salience by increasing wm . Conversely, if fm is not observed\n1606\tagain, its salience gradually decreases through decay.\n1607\tFigure S3 visualizes representative trajectories from three movies: Signs, Battle: Los Angeles, and Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. For each movie we\n1608\tplot two facts: a persistent narrative cue (solid line) and a transient observation\n1609\t(dashed line). These trajectories illustrate how StoryTeller selectively retains\n1610\tstory-relevant information while allowing short-lived visual details to fade from\n1611\tmemory.\n1612\t\n1613\tS5.1\n1614\t\n1615\tMemory Weight Evolution\n1616\t\n1617\tFigure S3 highlights two characteristic patterns of the memory update mechanism. Solid curves correspond to persistent narrative facts whose weights\n1618\tincrease when similar visual evidence appears in later scenes. Dashed curves correspond to transient observations that occur only once and therefore decay\n1619\twhen they are not reinforced. Star markers indicate scene indices selected for\n1620\tthe qualitative examples shown in Fig. S4.\n1621\tSigns. In Signs, the persistent fact corresponds to the interaction between the\n1622\tchildren and the family dog near the farmhouse porch. Because similar configurations recur across several scenes, the memory module repeatedly reinforces\n1623\tthis fact, resulting in a steadily increasing weight. In contrast, a transient observation involving Bo grilling food outside appears only briefly and is never\n1624\trevisited, causing the associated weight to decay rapidly.\n1625\t\n1626\t\f8\n1627\t\n1628\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1629\t\n1630\t(a) Signs\n1631\t\n1632\t(b) Battle: Los Angeles\n1633\t\n1634\t(c) Goblet of Fire\n1635\t\n1636\t(t)\n1637\t\n1638\tFig. S3: Memory-weight trajectories wm for representative facts fm extracted from\n1639\tSigns, Battle: Los Angeles, and Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. Solid curves denote persistent narrative cues that reappear across multiple scenes and therefore\n1640\treceive repeated reinforcement by the memory update mechanism. Dashed curves denote transient observations that occur only once and gradually decay when they are\n1641\tnot reinforced. Star markers indicate the scene indices used in the qualitative case studies shown in Fig. S4, where the corresponding video frames and StoryTeller-generated\n1642\taudio descriptions are displayed.\n1643\t\n1644\tBattle: Los Angeles. For Battle: Los Angeles, the persistent fact captures the\n1645\tsquad advancing through a dark, smoke-filled environment while protecting civilians. Multiple neighboring scenes depict variations of this tactical situation, leading to repeated reinforcement and a sustained memory weight. By comparison,\n1646\ta brief close-up of a wounded soldier appears only once during the moment and\n1647\tquickly fades from memory.\n1648\tHarry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. The third example contrasts a brief forest insert with a repeated corridor sequence. The persistent fact corresponds to\n1649\tHarry being escorted through a stone corridor by Moody. Each return to the hallway configuration reinforces the stored fact and increases its weight. The forest\n1650\tinsert, however, functions only as a short atmospheric transition and therefore\n1651\tdecays quickly.\n1652\tS5.2\n1653\t\n1654\tCase Study\n1655\t\n1656\tWhile the weight trajectories reveal how narrative facts evolve in memory, the\n1657\tqualitative examples in Fig. S4 illustrate how this salience affects the generated\n1658\taudio descriptions.\n1659\tEach panel presents representative frames together with the narration generated by StoryTeller. Words highlighted in red correspond to persistent narrative\n1660\tcues whose memory weights remain high across multiple scenes. Because these\n1661\tfacts remain salient, StoryTeller continues referencing the same narrative context\n1662\teven when the camera framing shifts or visual details change.\n1663\tFor example, in Signs, the generated description consistently refers to the\n1664\tinteraction between the children and the dog despite changes in viewpoint. Similarly, in Battle: Los Angeles, the narration preserves the context of soldiers advancing through smoke-filled interiors while protecting civilians. In Harry Potter\n1665\t\n1666\t\fStoryTeller\n1667\t\n1668\t9\n1669\t\n1670\tFig. S4: Representative frames corresponding to the facts highlighted in Fig. S3, together with StoryTeller-generated audio descriptions. Persistent narrative cues (highlighted in red) remain relevant across multiple scenes and are reinforced by the memory\n1671\tmechanism. Transient observations (highlighted in blue) appear only briefly and quickly\n1672\tdecay.\n1673\t\n1674\tand the Goblet of Fire, repeated corridor shots reinforce the interaction between\n1675\tHarry and Moody as they move through the dim stone corridor.\n1676\tIn contrast, words highlighted in blue correspond to transient visual details\n1677\tthat appear only briefly. Because these observations are not reinforced by later\n1678\tscenes, their memory weights decay and they do not influence subsequent descriptions.\n1679\tThese examples demonstrate the intended behavior of the StoryTeller memory mechanism: facts tied to ongoing narrative context accumulate weight and\n1680\tremain retrievable across scenes, while isolated observations gradually fade. This\n1681\tselective retention enables the system to maintain story-level continuity without\n1682\toverloading the memory with short-lived details.\n1683\t\n1684\t\f10\n1685\t\n1686\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1687\t\n1688\tS6\n1689\t\n1690\tBackbone Model Comparison\n1691\t\n1692\tWe compare StoryTeller with two generation backbones to separate architectural effects from backbone choice. The VideoLLaMA2 row corresponds to the\n1693\tStoryAD-QA setting reported in the main narrative-evaluation table, while the\n1694\tQwen3-VL row corresponds to the default implementation used for the Qwen3VL MAD-Eval result in the main comparison table.\n1695\tTable S4: Comparison of different VLM backbones. StoryAD-QA results are reported\n1696\tas accuracy (%) for Track A (blue shade) and Track B (orange shade).\n1697\tBackbone\n1698\t\n1699\tQwen3-VL\n1700\tVideoLLaMA2\n1701\t\n1702\tS7\n1703\t\n1704\tCIDEr\n1705\t\n1706\t21.4\n1707\t19.1\n1708\t\n1709\tStoryAD-QA Accuracy (%)\n1710\t30s\n1711\t\n1712\t60s\n1713\t\n1714\t120s\n1715\t\n1716\t240s\n1717\t\n1718\t30+30\n1719\t\n1720\t60+30\n1721\t\n1722\t90+30\n1723\t\n1724\t89.2\n1725\t85.9\n1726\t\n1727\t92.8\n1728\t90.2\n1729\t\n1730\t95.3\n1731\t92.9\n1732\t\n1733\t97.2\n1734\t95.4\n1735\t\n1736\t75.4\n1737\t72.7\n1738\t\n1739\t71.6\n1740\t70.9\n1741\t\n1742\t78.8\n1743\t72.4\n1744\t\n1745\tAdditional Evaluation on MovieChat\n1746\t\n1747\tWe additionally evaluate StoryTeller on a subset of the MovieChat-1K test\n1748\tset [3], containing 9 videos and 27 questions. Table S5 compares methods under\n1749\tthe input modality appropriate to each setting. MovieChat follows the standard MovieChat setup and accordingly receives the original source video (visual\n1750\tmodality) as input. In contrast, AutoAD-Zero and StoryTeller are AD-generation\n1751\tsystems, so we evaluate them by replacing the video with their generated AD\n1752\ttext and asking the same LLM answerer to answer the MovieChat questions from\n1753\ttext alone. This measures how much long-video QA information is preserved in\n1754\tthe generated descriptions.\n1755\tFor a fair no-curated-resource comparison between AD systems, AutoADZero is evaluated without its character bank, and StoryTeller is evaluated without public IMDb metadata. We also report StoryTeller with IMDb metadata to\n1756\tmeasure the additional benefit of public movie context. As shown in Table S5,\n1757\tStoryTeller outperforms AutoAD-Zero under the same generated-AD input setting, remains strong without IMDb metadata, and improves further when public\n1758\tmetadata is available. StoryAD-QA remains our primary narrative benchmark\n1759\tbecause it provides denser coverage of story events, with approximately one\n1760\tquestion per 30s compared with three questions per movie in this MovieChat\n1761\tsubset.\n1762\t\n1763\tS8\n1764\t\n1765\tStoryAD-QA Benchmark Overview and Validation\n1766\t\n1767\tThis section provides additional details about the construction and validation\n1768\tof the StoryAD-QA benchmark introduced in Section 4 of the main paper. We\n1769\t\n1770\t\fStoryTeller\n1771\t\n1772\t11\n1773\t\n1774\tTable S5: Additional evaluation on MovieChat The subset contains 9 videos\n1775\tand 27 questions. The subset contains 9 videos and 27 questions. MovieChat† uses the\n1776\toriginal source video, while AutoAD-Zero and StoryTeller use generated AD text as\n1777\tinput to the same LLM answerer.\n1778\tMethod\n1779\t\n1780\tInput\n1781\t\n1782\tAcc.\n1783\t\n1784\tScore\n1785\t\n1786\tMovieChat\n1787\tHuman reference caption\n1788\tAutoAD-Zero (no character bank)\n1789\tStoryTeller (no IMDb)\n1790\tStoryTeller (with IMDb)\n1791\t\n1792\tSource video\n1793\tShort caption\n1794\tGenerated AD\n1795\tGenerated AD\n1796\tGenerated AD\n1797\t\n1798\t0.623\n1799\t0.037\n1800\t0.704\n1801\t0.741\n1802\t0.778\n1803\t\n1804\t3.230\n1805\t0.185\n1806\t3.593\n1807\t3.778\n1808\t3.852\n1809\t\n1810\tTable S6: Distribution of the 2,574 questions in StoryAD-QA across evaluation tracks\n1811\tand segment durations. Track A uses only the target segment, while Track B provides\n1812\ta 30, 60, or 90-second preceding context window plus a fixed 30-second target segment.\n1813\tTrack\n1814\tTrack A (segment-only QA)\n1815\t\n1816\tSegment Duration # Questions\n1817\t30s\n1818\t60s\n1819\t120s\n1820\t240s\n1821\t\n1822\tTrack A Total\n1823\tTrack B (context-conditioned QA)\n1824\t\n1825\t860\n1826\t430\n1827\t212\n1828\t109\n1829\t1,611\n1830\t\n1831\t30s context + 30s\n1832\t60s context + 30s\n1833\t90s context + 30s\n1834\t\n1835\tTrack B Total\n1836\t\n1837\t449\n1838\t294\n1839\t220\n1840\t963\n1841\t\n1842\tsummarize the distribution of question types and segment durations, describe the\n1843\tmanual verification protocol used for all retained questions, and report validation\n1844\trates and annotation consistency.\n1845\tS8.1\n1846\t\n1847\tBenchmark Overview and Statistics\n1848\t\n1849\tTable S6 summarizes the distribution of the final retained StoryAD-QA questions\n1850\tacross the two evaluation tracks. Track A evaluates models using only the target\n1851\tsegment, while Track B requires additional narrative context from preceding\n1852\tsegments.\n1853\tTo capture events unfolding across multiple shots, we construct segments\n1854\tby grouping consecutive clips into temporal windows of varying duration. In\n1855\tTrack A, questions are associated with segments ranging from 30 to 240 seconds. In Track B, each question is paired with a 30-second target segment and\n1856\tan additional context window preceding it, encouraging models to reason over\n1857\tnarrative dependencies across segments.\n1858\t\n1859\t\f12\n1860\t\n1861\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1862\t\n1863\tFig. S5: Annotation interface used for human evaluation. Annotators watch the video\n1864\tsegment, review the multiple-choice question and answer options, and record judgments\n1865\tfor several verification criteria.\n1866\t\n1867\tAnswer Randomization. To prevent positional bias from the model generating\n1868\tthe questions, the answer options are randomly shuffled before being provided\n1869\tto the language model during evaluation.\n1870\tAPI Usage. Although the API safety filters were set to the least restrictive\n1871\tavailable configuration, a small number of AD inputs were still blocked by the\n1872\tservice and could not be processed. These instances were treated as missing\n1873\tvalues and excluded from aggregate results.\n1874\tS8.2\n1875\t\n1876\tManual Verification\n1877\t\n1878\tAll questions retained in StoryAD-QA are manually verified before inclusion.\n1879\tEach question is reviewed through a custom Gradio annotation interface, which\n1880\tpresents annotators with the corresponding video segment together with the\n1881\tgenerated question, answer options, the labeled correct answer, and the accompanying rationale produced during question generation. Figure S5 demonstrates\n1882\tthe interface from where annotators watch the corresponding video segment and\n1883\tthe corresponding generated questions and submit their evaluation of several\n1884\tquality metrics designed to assess the integrity of the question–answer pairs.\n1885\tThe review covers both the question and its answer set: annotators check that\n1886\tthe question is visually grounded and unambiguous, that the labeled answer is\n1887\tuniquely supported by the video evidence, and that the distractor options are\n1888\tplausible but incorrect. Questions that fail verification are discarded or regenerated and then checked again before they can enter the final benchmark.\n1889\tVerification criteria We use Correct answer to assess whether the labeled\n1890\tanswer is correct and uniquely supported by the visual evidence in the clip. In\n1891\taddition, we adopt two quality metrics from [2]. Visually grounded evaluates\n1892\twhether the correct answer can be determined solely from the visual content of\n1893\tthe clip, without relying on dialogue, audio, or external knowledge. Plausible\n1894\t\n1895\t\fStoryTeller\n1896\t\n1897\t13\n1898\t\n1899\tTable S7: Human verification results on all questions of the initial StoryAD-QA benchmark questions. Rates report the proportion of questions satisfying each criterion.\n1900\tSetting\n1901\t\n1902\tGrounded\n1903\t\n1904\tPlausible Distractors\n1905\t\n1906\tCorrect Ans.\n1907\t\n1908\tTrack A\n1909\t30 s\n1910\t60 s\n1911\t120 s\n1912\t240 s\n1913\t\n1914\t0.890\n1915\t0.901\n1916\t0.892\n1917\t0.963\n1918\t\n1919\t0.857\n1920\t0.875\n1921\t0.887\n1922\t0.936\n1923\t\n1924\t0.752\n1925\t0.795\n1926\t0.814\n1927\t0.833\n1928\t\n1929\tTrack B\n1930\t60 s\n1931\t90 s\n1932\t120 s\n1933\t\n1934\t0.838\n1935\t0.822\n1936\t0.886\n1937\t\n1938\t0.827\n1939\t0.784\n1940\t0.831\n1941\t\n1942\t0.744\n1943\t0.703\n1944\t0.699\n1945\t\n1946\tUnsure\n1947\t\n1948\t3\n1949\t\n1950\t3\n1951\t\n1952\t45\n1953\t\n1954\tdistractors assesses whether the incorrect answer options constitute realistic\n1955\talternatives that could reasonably be confused with the correct answer given the\n1956\tscene.\n1957\tIn addition to the binary Yes/No labels, annotators could also select Unsure\n1958\twhen the judgment was genuinely ambiguous. The verification statistics for the\n1959\tfull benchmark are presented in Table Tab. S7.\n1960\tS8.3\n1961\t\n1962\tQuestion Regeneration\n1963\t\n1964\tQuestions that received a negative rating in any evaluation criterion during the\n1965\tinitial human verification were discarded and regenerated using the same video\n1966\tclip and prompt, but with a stronger VLM, namely Gemini 3.5 Flash. In total,\n1967\twe regenerated 773 questions, of which 618 were retained after filtering out clips\n1968\tthat the VLM determined lacked sufficient information to support a meaningful\n1969\tquestion. All regenerated questions then underwent a second round of manual\n1970\tverification by a human annotator. Every question in this pass was accepted and\n1971\tincluded in the final benchmark.\n1972\t\n1973\tS9\n1974\t\n1975\tHuman Evaluation of Audio Descriptions\n1976\t\n1977\tTo evaluate the perceptual quality of generated audio descriptions, we conducted\n1978\ta human study comparing StoryTeller with AutoAD-Zero.\n1979\tS9.1\n1980\t\n1981\tStudy Setup\n1982\t\n1983\tWe randomly sampled 50 clips from the evaluation set, each with an average duration of approximately 20 seconds. For each clip, three annotators watched the\n1984\tvideo and compared two candidate audio descriptions: one generated by StoryTeller and one generated by AutoAD-Zero. The descriptions were presented with\n1985\t\n1986\t\f14\n1987\t\n1988\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n1989\t\n1990\tFig. S6: Human evaluation interface used in the study. Annotators watch a video clip\n1991\tand compare two candidate audio descriptions (Option A and Option B), whose order\n1992\tis randomized per trial. They select whether one description is better, whether the two\n1993\tare comparable (Tie), or whether both descriptions are inadequate.\n1994\t\n1995\tanonymized labels (Option A and Option B ), and their order was randomized\n1996\tfor each trial to avoid positional bias. Because each clip spans approximately 20\n1997\tseconds, the candidate descriptions are formed by concatenating multiple consecutive AD sentences generated for that clip, resulting in short multi-sentence\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"206fc7a5-df8a-4bee-9d63-61742ae2bbd5","uuid":"5691e46e-c65f-4fba-b3a5-4223302dd1b4","timestamp":"2026-07-14T11:38:59.425Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_2607_11798.txt","content":"\n240s\n\nDefault\n\n21.4\n\n89.2\n\n92.8\n\n95.3\n\n97.2\n\nα -20%\nα +20%\n\n20.2\n21.0\n\n89.4\n90.5\n\n94.4\n94.4\n\n96.2\n97.2\n\n97.2\n98.2\n\nλ -5%\nλ +5%\n\n21.9\n21.8\n\n89.7\n90.1\n\n94.2\n94.0\n\n95.3\n94.8\n\n97.2\n96.3\n\nIdentity Threshold (τ ). Identity assignment uses a fixed cosine similarity\nthreshold of τ = 0.58 for ArcFace embeddings. This value was selected empirically to balance missed associations and incorrect identity merges, and is kept\nfixed across all experiments.\nHyperparameter Robustness. Although StoryTeller introduces several global\nhyperparameters (identity threshold τ , grounding threshold σ, reinforcement\nstrength α, and decay rate λ), these are fixed once and not tuned on evaluation\ndata. To assess robustness, we vary α within ±20% and λ within ±5% while\nkeeping the remaining parameters fixed. Performance on the test split remains\nstable, with StoryAD-QA accuracy varying by less than 3 percentage points and\nCIDEr by less than 6 percentage points. Results are summarized in Table S3.\nS4.3\n\nMemory Overhead of Identity Reseeding\n\nIdentity reseeding maintains a small backlog of unresolved (anonymous) tracklets until sufficient evidence is available for identity assignment. Each unresolved tracklet stores a single 512-dimensional ArcFace embedding (approximately 2 KB). Across all movies in our experiments, retaining this anonymous\nbacklog required less than 3.5 MB per movie, indicating that delayed identity\nassignment introduces negligible memory overhead.\nS4.4\n\nLimitations and Discussion\n\nStoryTeller maintains consistent character references using the identity graph\ndescribed in Section 3.1 of the main paper which associates face tracklets across\nclips through clustering and similarity-based assignment. In rare cases, clustering\nerrors may temporarily associate a tracklet with the wrong identity. When this\noccurs, the generated description may mention an incorrect character name for\nthe corresponding scene.\nBecause StoryTeller maintains a persistent narrative state, such errors can\noften be corrected when stronger visual or narrative evidence becomes available.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n7\n\nIn particular, the reseeding mechanism described in Section 3.1 of the main\npaper allows identities to be updated once additional observations clarify the\ncharacter assignment. However, if incorrect associations persist across several\nclips, the resulting descriptions may temporarily reduce narrative accuracy.\nInterestingly, this behavior also highlights the importance of maintaining an\nexplicit narrative memory rather than relying solely on frame-level captioning.\nBy storing and updating structured narrative facts over time, the system can\nrevise earlier assumptions and maintain consistent story context as additional\nevidence appears. Future work may further improve robustness by integrating\nstronger identity verification or multimodal reasoning mechanisms.\n\nS5\n\nAnalysis of Narrative Memory Dynamics\n\nTo better understand how StoryTeller maintains narrative context across long\nvideo sequences, we analyze the evolution of memory weights associated with\nverified narrative facts. Each fact fm stored in the narrative memory is associated\n(t)\nwith a salience weight wm that reflects its current narrative importance. When\nlater scenes provide visual or semantic evidence supporting fm , the memory\n(t)\nmodule reinforces its salience by increasing wm . Conversely, if fm is not observed\nagain, its salience gradually decreases through decay.\nFigure S3 visualizes representative trajectories from three movies: Signs, Battle: Los Angeles, and Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. For each movie we\nplot two facts: a persistent narrative cue (solid line) and a transient observation\n(dashed line). These trajectories illustrate how StoryTeller selectively retains\nstory-relevant information while allowing short-lived visual details to fade from\nmemory.\n\nS5.1\n\nMemory Weight Evolution\n\nFigure S3 highlights two characteristic patterns of the memory update mechanism. Solid curves correspond to persistent narrative facts whose weights\nincrease when similar visual evidence appears in later scenes. Dashed curves correspond to transient observations that occur only once and therefore decay\nwhen they are not reinforced. Star markers indicate scene indices selected for\nthe qualitative examples shown in Fig. S4.\nSigns. In Signs, the persistent fact corresponds to the interaction between the\nchildren and the family dog near the farmhouse porch. Because similar configurations recur across several scenes, the memory module repeatedly reinforces\nthis fact, resulting in a steadily increasing weight. In contrast, a transient observation involving Bo grilling food outside appears only briefly and is never\nrevisited, causing the associated weight to decay rapidly.\n\n\f8\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\n(a) Signs\n\n(b) Battle: Los Angeles\n\n(c) Goblet of Fire\n\n(t)\n\nFig. S3: Memory-weight trajectories wm for representative facts fm extracted from\nSigns, Battle: Los Angeles, and Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. Solid curves denote persistent narrative cues that reappear across multiple scenes and therefore\nreceive repeated reinforcement by the memory update mechanism. Dashed curves denote transient observations that occur only once and gradually decay when they are\nnot reinforced. Star markers indicate the scene indices used in the qualitative case studies shown in Fig. S4, where the corresponding video frames and StoryTeller-generated\naudio descriptions are displayed.\n\nBattle: Los Angeles. For Battle: Los Angeles, the persistent fact captures the\nsquad advancing through a dark, smoke-filled environment while protecting civilians. Multiple neighboring scenes depict variations of this tactical situation, leading to repeated reinforcement and a sustained memory weight. By comparison,\na brief close-up of a wounded soldier appears only once during the moment and\nquickly fades from memory.\nHarry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. The third example contrasts a brief forest insert with a repeated corridor sequence. The persistent fact corresponds to\nHarry being escorted through a stone corridor by Moody. Each return to the hallway configuration reinforces the stored fact and increases its weight. The forest\ninsert, however, functions only as a short atmospheric transition and therefore\ndecays quickly.\nS5.2\n\nCase Study\n\nWhile the weight trajectories reveal how narrative facts evolve in memory, the\nqualitative examples in Fig. S4 illustrate how this salience affects the generated\naudio descriptions.\nEach panel presents representative frames together with the narration generated by StoryTeller. Words highlighted in red correspond to persistent narrative\ncues whose memory weights remain high across multiple scenes. Because these\nfacts remain salient, StoryTeller continues referencing the same narrative context\neven when the camera framing shifts or visual details change.\nFor example, in Signs, the generated description consistently refers to the\ninteraction between the children and the dog despite changes in viewpoint. Similarly, in Battle: Los Angeles, the narration preserves the context of soldiers advancing through smoke-filled interiors while protecting civilians. In Harry Potter\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n9\n\nFig. S4: Representative frames corresponding to the facts highlighted in Fig. S3, together with StoryTeller-generated audio descriptions. Persistent narrative cues (highlighted in red) remain relevant across multiple scenes and are reinforced by the memory\nmechanism. Transient observations (highlighted in blue) appear only briefly and quickly\ndecay.\n\nand the Goblet of Fire, repeated corridor shots reinforce the interaction between\nHarry and Moody as they move through the dim stone corridor.\nIn contrast, words highlighted in blue correspond to transient visual details\nthat appear only briefly. Because these observations are not reinforced by later\nscenes, their memory weights decay and they do not influence subsequent descriptions.\nThese examples demonstrate the intended behavior of the StoryTeller memory mechanism: facts tied to ongoing narrative context accumulate weight and\nremain retrievable across scenes, while isolated observations gradually fade. This\nselective retention enables the system to maintain story-level continuity without\noverloading the memory with short-lived details.\n\n\f10\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nS6\n\nBackbone Model Comparison\n\nWe compare StoryTeller with two generation backbones to separate architectural effects from backbone choice. The VideoLLaMA2 row corresponds to the\nStoryAD-QA setting reported in the main narrative-evaluation table, while the\nQwen3-VL row corresponds to the default implementation used for the Qwen3VL MAD-Eval result in the main comparison table.\nTable S4: Comparison of different VLM backbones. StoryAD-QA results are reported\nas accuracy (%) for Track A (blue shade) and Track B (orange shade).\nBackbone\n\nQwen3-VL\nVideoLLaMA2\n\nS7\n\nCIDEr\n\n21.4\n19.1\n\nStoryAD-QA Accuracy (%)\n30s\n\n60s\n\n120s\n\n240s\n\n30+30\n\n60+30\n\n90+30\n\n89.2\n85.9\n\n92.8\n90.2\n\n95.3\n92.9\n\n97.2\n95.4\n\n75.4\n72.7\n\n71.6\n70.9\n\n78.8\n72.4\n\nAdditional Evaluation on MovieChat\n\nWe additionally evaluate StoryTeller on a subset of the MovieChat-1K test\nset [3], containing 9 videos and 27 questions. Table S5 compares methods under\nthe input modality appropriate to each setting. MovieChat follows the standard MovieChat setup and accordingly receives the original source video (visual\nmodality) as input. In contrast, AutoAD-Zero and StoryTeller are AD-generation\nsystems, so we evaluate them by replacing the video with their generated AD\ntext and asking the same LLM answerer to answer the MovieChat questions from\ntext alone. This measures how much long-video QA information is preserved in\nthe generated descriptions.\nFor a fair no-curated-resource comparison between AD systems, AutoADZero is evaluated without its character bank, and StoryTeller is evaluated without public IMDb metadata. We also report StoryTeller with IMDb metadata to\nmeasure the additional benefit of public movie context. As shown in Table S5,\nStoryTeller outperforms AutoAD-Zero under the same generated-AD input setting, remains strong without IMDb metadata, and improves further when public\nmetadata is available. StoryAD-QA remains our primary narrative benchmark\nbecause it provides denser coverage of story events, with approximately one\nquestion per 30s compared with three questions per movie in this MovieChat\nsubset.\n\nS8\n\nStoryAD-QA Benchmark Overview and Validation\n\nThis section provides additional details about the construction and validation\nof the StoryAD-QA benchmark introduced in Section 4 of the main paper. We\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n11\n\nTable S5: Additional evaluation on MovieChat The subset contains 9 videos\nand 27 questions. The subset contains 9 videos and 27 questions. MovieChat† uses the\noriginal source video, while AutoAD-Zero and StoryTeller use generated AD text as\ninput to the same LLM answerer.\nMethod\n\nInput\n\nAcc.\n\nScore\n\nMovieChat\nHuman reference caption\nAutoAD-Zero (no character bank)\nStoryTeller (no IMDb)\nStoryTeller (with IMDb)\n\nSource video\nShort caption\nGenerated AD\nGenerated AD\nGenerated AD\n\n0.623\n0.037\n0.704\n0.741\n0.778\n\n3.230\n0.185\n3.593\n3.778\n3.852\n\nTable S6: Distribution of the 2,574 questions in StoryAD-QA across evaluation tracks\nand segment durations. Track A uses only the target segment, while Track B provides\na 30, 60, or 90-second preceding context window plus a fixed 30-second target segment.\nTrack\nTrack A (segment-only QA)\n\nSegment Duration # Questions\n30s\n60s\n120s\n240s\n\nTrack A Total\nTrack B (context-conditioned QA)\n\n860\n430\n212\n109\n1,611\n\n30s context + 30s\n60s context + 30s\n90s context + 30s\n\nTrack B Total\n\n449\n294\n220\n963\n\nsummarize the distribution of question types and segment durations, describe the\nmanual verification protocol used for all retained questions, and report validation\nrates and annotation consistency.\nS8.1\n\nBenchmark Overview and Statistics\n\nTable S6 summarizes the distribution of the final retained StoryAD-QA questions\nacross the two evaluation tracks. Track A evaluates models using only the target\nsegment, while Track B requires additional narrative context from preceding\nsegments.\nTo capture events unfolding across multiple shots, we construct segments\nby grouping consecutive clips into temporal windows of varying duration. In\nTrack A, questions are associated with segments ranging from 30 to 240 seconds. In Track B, each question is paired with a 30-second target segment and\nan additional context window preceding it, encouraging models to reason over\nnarrative dependencies across segments.\n\n\f12\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nFig. S5: Annotation interface used for human evaluation. Annotators watch the video\nsegment, review the multiple-choice question and answer options, and record judgments\nfor several verification criteria.\n\nAnswer Randomization. To prevent positional bias from the model generating\nthe questions, the answer options are randomly shuffled before being provided\nto the language model during evaluation.\nAPI Usage. Although the API safety filters were set to the least restrictive\navailable configuration, a small number of AD inputs were still blocked by the\nservice and could not be processed. These instances were treated as missing\nvalues and excluded from aggregate results.\nS8.2\n\nManual Verification\n\nAll questions retained in StoryAD-QA are manually verified before inclusion.\nEach question is reviewed through a custom Gradio annotation interface, which\npresents annotators with the corresponding video segment together with the\ngenerated question, answer options, the labeled correct answer, and the accompanying rationale produced during question generation. Figure S5 demonstrates\nthe interface from where annotators watch the corresponding video segment and\nthe corresponding generated questions and submit their evaluation of several\nquality metrics designed to assess the integrity of the question–answer pairs.\nThe review covers both the question and its answer set: annotators check that\nthe question is visually grounded and unambiguous, that the labeled answer is\nuniquely supported by the video evidence, and that the distractor options are\nplausible but incorrect. Questions that fail verification are discarded or regenerated and then checked again before they can enter the final benchmark.\nVerification criteria We use Correct answer to assess whether the labeled\nanswer is correct and uniquely supported by the visual evidence in the clip. In\naddition, we adopt two quality metrics from [2]. Visually grounded evaluates\nwhether the correct answer can be determined solely from the visual content of\nthe clip, without relying on dialogue, audio, or external knowledge. Plausible\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n13\n\nTable S7: Human verification results on all questions of the initial StoryAD-QA benchmark questions. Rates report the proportion of questions satisfying each criterion.\nSetting\n\nGrounded\n\nPlausible Distractors\n\nCorrect Ans.\n\nTrack A\n30 s\n60 s\n120 s\n240 s\n\n0.890\n0.901\n0.892\n0.963\n\n0.857\n0.875\n0.887\n0.936\n\n0.752\n0.795\n0.814\n0.833\n\nTrack B\n60 s\n90 s\n120 s\n\n0.838\n0.822\n0.886\n\n0.827\n0.784\n0.831\n\n0.744\n0.703\n0.699\n\nUnsure\n\n3\n\n3\n\n45\n\ndistractors assesses whether the incorrect answer options constitute realistic\nalternatives that could reasonably be confused with the correct answer given the\nscene.\nIn addition to the binary Yes/No labels, annotators could also select Unsure\nwhen the judgment was genuinely ambiguous. The verification statistics for the\nfull benchmark are presented in Table Tab. S7.\nS8.3\n\nQuestion Regeneration\n\nQuestions that received a negative rating in any evaluation criterion during the\ninitial human verification were discarded and regenerated using the same video\nclip and prompt, but with a stronger VLM, namely Gemini 3.5 Flash. In total,\nwe regenerated 773 questions, of which 618 were retained after filtering out clips\nthat the VLM determined lacked sufficient information to support a meaningful\nquestion. All regenerated questions then underwent a second round of manual\nverification by a human annotator. Every question in this pass was accepted and\nincluded in the final benchmark.\n\nS9\n\nHuman Evaluation of Audio Descriptions\n\nTo evaluate the perceptual quality of generated audio descriptions, we conducted\na human study comparing StoryTeller with AutoAD-Zero.\nS9.1\n\nStudy Setup\n\nWe randomly sampled 50 clips from the evaluation set, each with an average duration of approximately 20 seconds. For each clip, three annotators watched the\nvideo and compared two candidate audio descriptions: one generated by StoryTeller and one generated by AutoAD-Zero. The descriptions were presented with\n\n\f14\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nFig. S6: Human evaluation interface used in the study. Annotators watch a video clip\nand compare two candidate audio descriptions (Option A and Option B), whose order\nis randomized per trial. They select whether one description is better, whether the two\nare comparable (Tie), or whether both descriptions are inadequate.\n\nanonymized labels (Option A and Option B ), and their order was randomized\nfor each trial to avoid positional bias. Because each clip spans approximately 20\nseconds, the candidate descriptions are formed by concatenating multiple consecutive AD sentences generated for that clip, resulting in short multi-sentence","numLines":500,"startLine":1498,"totalLines":2339}}}
