{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-a2cebb9dcb6de176","type":"tool_result","content":"1997\tseconds, the candidate descriptions are formed by concatenating multiple consecutive AD sentences generated for that clip, resulting in short multi-sentence\n1998\tdescriptions.\n1999\tFigure S6 illustrates the evaluation interface. Annotators could replay the clip\n2000\tand optionally view the reference audio narration (ground truth) for additional\n2001\tcontext, but no system identifiers or auxiliary metadata were shown in order to\n2002\tmaintain a blind evaluation.\n2003\tFor each clip, annotators selected one of four options:\n2004\t– Option A better: description A provides a better audio description.\n2005\t– Option B better: description B provides a better audio description.\n2006\t– Tie: both descriptions are of comparable quality.\n2007\t– Both bad: neither description adequately describes the scene.\n2008\tAnnotators were instructed to judge descriptions based on two criteria: (i)\n2009\thow accurately the description reflects the visible content of the clip, and (ii)\n2010\twhether the narration conveys the scene clearly and coherently for a blind or\n2011\tlow-vision audience. The study involved three human evaluators, each rating all\n2012\t50 clips.\n2013\tS9.2\n2014\t\n2015\tResults\n2016\t\n2017\tTable S8 summarizes the human preference results. Across the 50 evaluated\n2018\tclips, annotators preferred StoryTeller substantially more often than AutoADZero, with StoryTeller receiving 76.0% of the preferences compared to 5.8% for\n2019\t\n2020\t\fStoryTeller\n2021\t\n2022\t15\n2023\t\n2024\tTable S8: Human preference comparison between StoryTeller and AutoAD-Zero.\n2025\tMethod\n2026\tPreference (%)\n2027\tStoryTeller\n2028\t76.0\n2029\tAutoAD-Zero\n2030\t5.8\n2031\tTie\n2032\t9.1\n2033\tBoth bad\n2034\t9.1\n2035\t\n2036\tthe baseline while 9.1% of the evaluations resulted ina tie and 9.1% judged both\n2037\tdescriptions inadequate.\n2038\tIn many cases, annotators selected StoryTeller when its descriptions captured\n2039\tscene context or environmental cues visible in the frames, whereas AutoAD-Zero\n2040\tdescriptions tended to focus on shorter or more generic actions.\n2041\t\n2042\tS10\n2043\t\n2044\tPrompt Templates\n2045\t\n2046\tThis section lists the prompt templates used in the StoryTeller pipeline, organized according to the modules described in Sec. 3 of the main paper: scene\n2047\tsummarization, structured fact extraction, fact verification, and narration generation. The prompts guide the model to distinguish observed evidence from\n2048\tauxiliary cues such as public movie metadata. In particular, the fact-extraction\n2049\tschema records whether each candidate fact is suggested by visual, audio, or\n2050\tmetadata input. Metadata may help propose candidates, such as possible character names, but these candidates are passed through a separate verification step\n2051\tbefore being added to memory or used in narration.\n2052\tS10.1\n2053\t\n2054\tScene Summarization Prompt\n2055\t\n2056\tStage 1: Scene Summarization. This prompt generates a concise summary\n2057\tof the visual content of a single video clip. The goal of this stage is to produce\n2058\ta short, grounded description that captures the main observable event without\n2059\tintroducing speculative interpretation. The summary serves as the initial representation of the scene and is later expanded into structured narrative facts.\n2060\tInstruction. You create concise, evidence-grounded clip summaries for audio description. Rules: present tense; one sentence; less than 25 words; describe only what\n2061\tis clearly visible or audible; no speculation, no spoilers; if identity is unclear, use\n2062\tneutral labels.\n2063\tPrompt. Summarize the clip in one concise sentence, describing only what is clearly\n2064\tvisible or audible.\n2065\t\n2066\tS10.2\n2067\t\n2068\tStructured Fact Extraction Prompt\n2069\t\n2070\tStage 2: Structured Fact Extraction. Given the scene summary and video\n2071\tclip, this prompt extracts structured facts describing observable actions, entities,\n2072\t\n2073\t\f16\n2074\t\n2075\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n2076\t\n2077\tand locations. The output follows a strict JSON schema in order to produce\n2078\tatomic, verifiable facts that can be independently checked. These structured\n2079\tfacts form the basis of the narrative memory used by StoryTeller.\n2080\tInstruction. You extract structured, evidence-grounded facts from a video clip\n2081\tfor audio description. Return ONLY valid JSON exactly matching the schema. No\n2082\tmarkdown. No extra keys. No inference. Keep facts atomic (one action each) and\n2083\tlimit to 6 to 10 items. Use neutral labels if identity is unclear.\n2084\tFill the JSON schema below using only what is clearly visible or audible in the clip.\n2085\tSchema:\n2086\t{\n2087\t\"scene_summary\": \"one sentence visual summary\",\n2088\t\"time_window\": \"start-end seconds or mm:ss-mm:ss\",\n2089\t\"facts\": [\n2090\t{\n2091\t\"subject\": \"who performed the action\",\n2092\t\"action\": \"verb phrase\",\n2093\t\"object\": \"what/who was acted upon; use empty string if\n2094\tnot needed\",\n2095\t\"location\": \"where in the scene\",\n2096\t\"time\": \"timestamp or short range\",\n2097\t\"evidence\": \"visual|audio|metadata\",\n2098\t\"confidence\": \"high|medium|low\",\n2099\t\"notes\": \"optional clarifications\",\n2100\t\"cluster_id\": \"if the action involves a TRACKLET_GUIDE entry,\n2101\tcopy its tracklet_id (e.g., trk_0003)\",\n2102\t\"character_id\": \"when 100% certain,\n2103\tsupply the canonical character_id from metadata\"\n2104\t}\n2105\t],\n2106\t\"uncertain_observations\": [\"optional list describing ambiguities\"]\n2107\t}\n2108\tTRACKLET_GUIDE (cluster IDs visible in this clip): {tracklet_hint}\n2109\tSpoiler-safe metadata snippets that may match this moment: {context_snippets}\n2110\tMetadata hints for this movie (use only if they match the video): {metadata_hint}\n2111\t\n2112\tS10.3\n2113\t\n2114\tFact Verification Prompt\n2115\t\n2116\tStage 3: Fact Verification. To prevent hallucinated or weakly grounded observations from entering the memory, each extracted fact is passed through a\n2117\tverification step. The model acts as a strict fact checker and determines whether\n2118\tthe proposed fact is clearly supported by the visual evidence in the clip. Only\n2119\taccepted facts are retained for downstream narration.\n2120\t\n2121\t\fStoryTeller\n2122\t\n2123\t17\n2124\t\n2125\tInstruction. You are a strict video-grounded fact checker. Accept only if the clip\n2126\tclearly supports the fact. If ambiguous, inferred, off-screen, or not shown: reject.\n2127\tPrompt. You are verifying whether the FACT is truly visible or supported in this\n2128\tvideo clip. Use the video as the primary source. On the first line respond exactly\n2129\twith either ACCEPT or REJECT, then provide a one-sentence justification citing\n2130\twhat you observed.\n2131\tFACT: {fact_text}\n2132\t\n2133\tS10.4\n2134\t\n2135\tFinal Input Prompt\n2136\t\n2137\tStage 4: Final Narration Generation. The final prompt produces the audio\n2138\tdescription used for evaluation. It conditions on the verified fact set and optional\n2139\tnarrative memory context from previous clips. The prompt instructs the model\n2140\tto generate a concise, visually grounded narration that reflects the scene while\n2141\tavoiding references to cameras or recording artifacts.\n2142\tInstruction. You are an in-scene narrator describing events to blind or low-vision\n2143\tlisteners. Deliver the narration as a storyteller within the world of the film. Never\n2144\tmention cameras, screens, or phrases such as “in this video,” “on screen,” “toward the\n2145\tcamera,” or “looks at the camera.” If a draft would mention recording equipment,\n2146\trewrite it so the line instead describes how characters relate to one another or to\n2147\ttheir environment.\n2148\tRely on grounded details from the FACT_BLOCK, keep the chronology clear,\n2149\tand favor concise active sentences. When a FACT_BLOCK entry includes a\n2150\tcharacter_id, refer to that person by the provided first name only. Do not invent\n2151\tor guess names. Use the provided first name when the character is first mentioned;\n2152\tafterwards, pronouns such as he, she, or they may be used.\n2153\tHighlight motion, intent, and key sounds. Omit filler and self-referential phrasing.\n2154\tKeep the final description under 20 words. Use MEMORY_CONTEXT only when\n2155\tit directly supports continuity without speculation.\n2156\tClip duration: {duration:.2f}s\n2157\tOutput format: Return JSON in the form {\"summarised_AD\": \"... \"}.\n2158\tExamples. For a 0.8s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"She looks at Riker.\"}\n2159\tFor a 1.4s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Paul looks at his wife lovingly.\"}\n2160\tFor a 2.6s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Returning to the room, Sarah peers\n2161\tinto the darkness.\"}\n2162\tFor a 3.5s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Stephen looks at Sara as she walks to\n2163\tthe door.\"}\n2164\t\n2165\tS10.5\n2166\t\n2167\tStoryAD-QA Question Generation Prompt\n2168\t\n2169\tTrack A (segment-only QA). The Track A prompt asks the VLM to generate a multiple-choice question about the main visual event within a single clip.\n2170\tFor question generation only, the VLM also receives a short Wikipedia movie\n2171\toverview as background. The prompt explicitly restricts the model to information that is directly visible, prohibits the use of dialogue, external knowledge, or\n2172\t\n2173\t\f18\n2174\t\n2175\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n2176\t\n2177\tspeculative reasoning, and requires a short rationale grounded in visual evidence.\n2178\tIf the clip does not contain a clear self-contained event, the model is instructed\n2179\tto output SKIP.\n2180\tYou are given:\n2181\t- A video clip from a movie.\n2182\t- A movie overview for background context only.\n2183\tOverview: {movie_overview}\n2184\tIMPORTANT: This clip may still be incomplete relative to the full movie. Do\n2185\tNOT assume anything outside what is visible in this clip. Do NOT use prior\n2186\tknowledge of the movie, characters, or story. Use only what is directly shown.\n2187\tTASK: Your task is to generate ONE 5-option multiple-choice question about the\n2188\tmain visual event or progression shown in this clip. If the clip does NOT contain\n2189\ta clear, self-contained action, reaction, reveal, or cause–effect moment that is fully\n2190\tshown, output:\n2191\tSKIP\n2192\tThe question MUST reflect the main development of the clip, not a small detail\n2193\tfrom a brief moment. Focus on the most important or climactic visible event.\n2194\tDo NOT generate a question if:\n2195\t- The moment is routine or transitional\n2196\t- The answer depends on events outside this clip\n2197\t- It requires guessing thoughts, intentions, or emotions\n2198\t- It relies on what happens before or after the clip\n2199\tIf uncertain, output:\n2200\tSKIP\n2201\tRequirements:\n2202\t- 1–2 sentence question\n2203\t- Answerable using only this clip\n2204\t- No “Why” questions\n2205\t- No references to before or after the clip\n2206\t- No psychological interpretation\n2207\t- Focus on clearly visible actions or outcomes\n2208\tAll incorrect options must be plausible.\n2209\tOutput format:\n2210\tQuestion:\n2211\t<question>\n2212\tA.\n2213\tB.\n2214\tC.\n2215\tD.\n2216\tE.\n2217\t\n2218\t\fStoryTeller\n2219\t\n2220\t19\n2221\t\n2222\tCorrect Answer: <letter>\n2223\tRationale:\n2224\t<1–2 sentences describing only visible evidence>\n2225\t\n2226\tTrack B (context-conditioned QA). The Track B prompt introduces an\n2227\texplicit separation between a context window and a target scene. The context\n2228\tmay introduce entities or situations, but the correct answer must be visually verifiable in the target scene. The prompt further discourages references to timestamps, dialogue, or outside knowledge to ensure questions remain grounded in\n2229\tobservable visual information.\n2230\tYou are given a movie video clip and a brief movie overview for background only.\n2231\tOverview: {movie_overview}\n2232\tThe first {context_len} seconds of the clip are CONTEXT.\n2233\tThe remaining part of the clip is the TARGET SCENE.\n2234\tThe context may introduce people, objects, or locations that help interpret the\n2235\ttarget scene.\n2236\tGenerate ONE multiple-choice question (5 options A-E) that requires using the\n2237\tcontext to understand what is happening in the target scene.\n2238\tKey principle: The answer must be visible in the TARGET SCENE, but the\n2239\tCONTEXT should help identify or interpret the object, person, or situation referenced in the question.\n2240\tPreferred patterns:\n2241\t- An object or person appears in the context, and the question asks about its\n2242\tstate, action, or location in the target scene.\n2243\t- Something in the target scene is ambiguous unless the viewer remembers the\n2244\tcontext.\n2245\t- The context introduces an item or situation whose consequence or change\n2246\tbecomes visible in the target scene.\n2247\tRules:\n2248\t- The question must be answerable using only what is visibly shown in the video. The correct answer must be visually verifiable in the TARGET SCENE (after the\n2249\tfirst {context_len} seconds).\n2250\t- The context should help identify what the question refers to, but should not\n2251\tcontain the answer itself.\n2252\t- Do not rely on character names, dialogue, subtitles, or outside knowledge.\n2253\t- Focus on observable actions, objects, interactions, or spatial relationships.\n2254\t- Avoid trivial decorative details that do not affect the scene.\n2255\t- Do not ask “Why” questions or infer emotions, intentions, or story meaning.\n2256\t- Do not mention numeric timestamps, seconds, or \"the first {context_len}\n2257\tseconds\".\n2258\t- Do not refer to the video itself (no phrases like “in this clip” or “on screen”).\n2259\t\n2260\t\f20\n2261\t\n2262\tS. H. Hahm et al.\n2263\t\n2264\tThe question MUST reflect the main development of the clip, not a small detail\n2265\tfrom a brief moment. Focus on the most important or climactic visible event.\n2266\tDo NOT generate a question if:\n2267\t- The moment is routine or transitional\n2268\t- The answer depends on events outside this clip\n2269\t- It requires guessing thoughts, intentions, or emotions\n2270\t- It relies on what happens before or after the clip\n2271\tIf there is no clear visual moment after the context that connects to something\n2272\tintroduced earlier, output:\n2273\tSKIP\n2274\tOutput format:\n2275\tQuestion:\n2276\t<question>\n2277\tA. <option>\n2278\tB. <option>\n2279\tC. <option>\n2280\tD. <option>\n2281\tE. <option>\n2282\tCorrect Answer: <letter>\n2283\tRationale:\n2284\t<1–2 sentences describing only the visible evidence in the target\n2285\tscene that confirms the answer>\n2286\t\n2287\tS10.6\n2288\t\n2289\tStoryAD-QA Question Answering Prompt\n2290\t\n2291\tDuring evaluation, we provide the language model with only textual inputs:\n2292\tthe question and the corresponding audio descriptions for the scene. The model\n2293\tis instructed to select an answer using only the information contained in the\n2294\tAD, without the use of external knowledge, prior familiarity with the movie, or\n2295\tassumptions about events not described in the AD text. In addition, the model\n2296\tis required to produce a short rationale citing explicit evidence from the AD,\n2297\tencouraging answers that are grounded in the provided narration.\n2298\tTo reduce positional bias, the answer options are randomly shuffled before\n2299\tbeing presented to the language model during evaluation.\n2300\tYou are given:\n2301\t- Audio Descriptions (AD) for a movie scene.\n2302\t- A multiple-choice question about that scene.\n2303\t\n2304\t\fStoryTeller\n2305\t\n2306\t21\n2307\t\n2308\tQuestion:\n2309\t{question}\n2310\tAudio Descriptions (AD):\n2311\t{ad_text}\n2312\tIMPORTANT: Use only information explicitly stated in the AD text. Do NOT\n2313\tuse prior knowledge of the movie. Do NOT assume events outside the AD. Do\n2314\tNOT guess characters’ thoughts or intentions unless the AD explicitly states them.\n2315\tTASK: Select the best answer (A, B, C, D, or E) based only on the AD.\n2316\tOutput format:\n2317\tAnswer: <letter>\n2318\tRationale:\n2319\t<1–2 sentences citing only explicit AD evidence>\n2320\t\n2321\tReferences\n2322\t1. Deng, J., Guo, J., Xue, N., Zafeiriou, S.: Arcface: Additive angular margin loss for\n2323\tdeep face recognition. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer\n2324\tVision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 4690–4699 (2019)\n2325\t2. Kala, D., Khandelwal, E., Tapaswi, M.: What you see is what you ask: Evaluating\n2326\taudio descriptions. In: Christodoulopoulos, C., Chakraborty, T., Rose, C., Peng, V.\n2327\t(eds.) Proceedings of the Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language\n2328\tProcessing (EMNLP). pp. 23496–23518. Association for Computational Linguistics,\n2329\tSuzhou, China (Nov 2025). https://doi.org/10.18653/v1/2025.emnlp- main.\n2330\t1199, https://aclanthology.org/2025.emnlp-main.1199/\n2331\t3. Song, E., Chai, W., Wang, G., Zhang, Y., Zhou, H., Wu, F., Chi, H., Guo, X.,\n2332\tYe, T., Zhang, Y., Lu, Y., Hwang, J.N., Wang, G.: Moviechat: From dense token\n2333\tto sparse memory for long video understanding. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF\n2334\tConference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 18221–18232\n2335\t(June 2024)\n2336\t4. Xie, J., Han, T., Bain, M., Nagrani, A., Varol, G., Xie, W., Zisserman, A.: AutoADZero: A training-free framework for zero-shot audio description. In: Proceedings of\n2337\tthe Asian Conference on Computer Vision (ACCV). pp. 2265–2281 (2024)\n2338\t\n2339\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"206fc7a5-df8a-4bee-9d63-61742ae2bbd5","uuid":"b555e57e-78ba-4fee-b0f0-8460d95c731e","timestamp":"2026-07-14T11:39:24.604Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_2607_11798.txt","content":"seconds, the candidate descriptions are formed by concatenating multiple consecutive AD sentences generated for that clip, resulting in short multi-sentence\ndescriptions.\nFigure S6 illustrates the evaluation interface. Annotators could replay the clip\nand optionally view the reference audio narration (ground truth) for additional\ncontext, but no system identifiers or auxiliary metadata were shown in order to\nmaintain a blind evaluation.\nFor each clip, annotators selected one of four options:\n– Option A better: description A provides a better audio description.\n– Option B better: description B provides a better audio description.\n– Tie: both descriptions are of comparable quality.\n– Both bad: neither description adequately describes the scene.\nAnnotators were instructed to judge descriptions based on two criteria: (i)\nhow accurately the description reflects the visible content of the clip, and (ii)\nwhether the narration conveys the scene clearly and coherently for a blind or\nlow-vision audience. The study involved three human evaluators, each rating all\n50 clips.\nS9.2\n\nResults\n\nTable S8 summarizes the human preference results. Across the 50 evaluated\nclips, annotators preferred StoryTeller substantially more often than AutoADZero, with StoryTeller receiving 76.0% of the preferences compared to 5.8% for\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n15\n\nTable S8: Human preference comparison between StoryTeller and AutoAD-Zero.\nMethod\nPreference (%)\nStoryTeller\n76.0\nAutoAD-Zero\n5.8\nTie\n9.1\nBoth bad\n9.1\n\nthe baseline while 9.1% of the evaluations resulted ina tie and 9.1% judged both\ndescriptions inadequate.\nIn many cases, annotators selected StoryTeller when its descriptions captured\nscene context or environmental cues visible in the frames, whereas AutoAD-Zero\ndescriptions tended to focus on shorter or more generic actions.\n\nS10\n\nPrompt Templates\n\nThis section lists the prompt templates used in the StoryTeller pipeline, organized according to the modules described in Sec. 3 of the main paper: scene\nsummarization, structured fact extraction, fact verification, and narration generation. The prompts guide the model to distinguish observed evidence from\nauxiliary cues such as public movie metadata. In particular, the fact-extraction\nschema records whether each candidate fact is suggested by visual, audio, or\nmetadata input. Metadata may help propose candidates, such as possible character names, but these candidates are passed through a separate verification step\nbefore being added to memory or used in narration.\nS10.1\n\nScene Summarization Prompt\n\nStage 1: Scene Summarization. This prompt generates a concise summary\nof the visual content of a single video clip. The goal of this stage is to produce\na short, grounded description that captures the main observable event without\nintroducing speculative interpretation. The summary serves as the initial representation of the scene and is later expanded into structured narrative facts.\nInstruction. You create concise, evidence-grounded clip summaries for audio description. Rules: present tense; one sentence; less than 25 words; describe only what\nis clearly visible or audible; no speculation, no spoilers; if identity is unclear, use\nneutral labels.\nPrompt. Summarize the clip in one concise sentence, describing only what is clearly\nvisible or audible.\n\nS10.2\n\nStructured Fact Extraction Prompt\n\nStage 2: Structured Fact Extraction. Given the scene summary and video\nclip, this prompt extracts structured facts describing observable actions, entities,\n\n\f16\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nand locations. The output follows a strict JSON schema in order to produce\natomic, verifiable facts that can be independently checked. These structured\nfacts form the basis of the narrative memory used by StoryTeller.\nInstruction. You extract structured, evidence-grounded facts from a video clip\nfor audio description. Return ONLY valid JSON exactly matching the schema. No\nmarkdown. No extra keys. No inference. Keep facts atomic (one action each) and\nlimit to 6 to 10 items. Use neutral labels if identity is unclear.\nFill the JSON schema below using only what is clearly visible or audible in the clip.\nSchema:\n{\n\"scene_summary\": \"one sentence visual summary\",\n\"time_window\": \"start-end seconds or mm:ss-mm:ss\",\n\"facts\": [\n{\n\"subject\": \"who performed the action\",\n\"action\": \"verb phrase\",\n\"object\": \"what/who was acted upon; use empty string if\nnot needed\",\n\"location\": \"where in the scene\",\n\"time\": \"timestamp or short range\",\n\"evidence\": \"visual|audio|metadata\",\n\"confidence\": \"high|medium|low\",\n\"notes\": \"optional clarifications\",\n\"cluster_id\": \"if the action involves a TRACKLET_GUIDE entry,\ncopy its tracklet_id (e.g., trk_0003)\",\n\"character_id\": \"when 100% certain,\nsupply the canonical character_id from metadata\"\n}\n],\n\"uncertain_observations\": [\"optional list describing ambiguities\"]\n}\nTRACKLET_GUIDE (cluster IDs visible in this clip): {tracklet_hint}\nSpoiler-safe metadata snippets that may match this moment: {context_snippets}\nMetadata hints for this movie (use only if they match the video): {metadata_hint}\n\nS10.3\n\nFact Verification Prompt\n\nStage 3: Fact Verification. To prevent hallucinated or weakly grounded observations from entering the memory, each extracted fact is passed through a\nverification step. The model acts as a strict fact checker and determines whether\nthe proposed fact is clearly supported by the visual evidence in the clip. Only\naccepted facts are retained for downstream narration.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n17\n\nInstruction. You are a strict video-grounded fact checker. Accept only if the clip\nclearly supports the fact. If ambiguous, inferred, off-screen, or not shown: reject.\nPrompt. You are verifying whether the FACT is truly visible or supported in this\nvideo clip. Use the video as the primary source. On the first line respond exactly\nwith either ACCEPT or REJECT, then provide a one-sentence justification citing\nwhat you observed.\nFACT: {fact_text}\n\nS10.4\n\nFinal Input Prompt\n\nStage 4: Final Narration Generation. The final prompt produces the audio\ndescription used for evaluation. It conditions on the verified fact set and optional\nnarrative memory context from previous clips. The prompt instructs the model\nto generate a concise, visually grounded narration that reflects the scene while\navoiding references to cameras or recording artifacts.\nInstruction. You are an in-scene narrator describing events to blind or low-vision\nlisteners. Deliver the narration as a storyteller within the world of the film. Never\nmention cameras, screens, or phrases such as “in this video,” “on screen,” “toward the\ncamera,” or “looks at the camera.” If a draft would mention recording equipment,\nrewrite it so the line instead describes how characters relate to one another or to\ntheir environment.\nRely on grounded details from the FACT_BLOCK, keep the chronology clear,\nand favor concise active sentences. When a FACT_BLOCK entry includes a\ncharacter_id, refer to that person by the provided first name only. Do not invent\nor guess names. Use the provided first name when the character is first mentioned;\nafterwards, pronouns such as he, she, or they may be used.\nHighlight motion, intent, and key sounds. Omit filler and self-referential phrasing.\nKeep the final description under 20 words. Use MEMORY_CONTEXT only when\nit directly supports continuity without speculation.\nClip duration: {duration:.2f}s\nOutput format: Return JSON in the form {\"summarised_AD\": \"... \"}.\nExamples. For a 0.8s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"She looks at Riker.\"}\nFor a 1.4s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Paul looks at his wife lovingly.\"}\nFor a 2.6s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Returning to the room, Sarah peers\ninto the darkness.\"}\nFor a 3.5s clip: {\"summarised_AD\": \"Stephen looks at Sara as she walks to\nthe door.\"}\n\nS10.5\n\nStoryAD-QA Question Generation Prompt\n\nTrack A (segment-only QA). The Track A prompt asks the VLM to generate a multiple-choice question about the main visual event within a single clip.\nFor question generation only, the VLM also receives a short Wikipedia movie\noverview as background. The prompt explicitly restricts the model to information that is directly visible, prohibits the use of dialogue, external knowledge, or\n\n\f18\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nspeculative reasoning, and requires a short rationale grounded in visual evidence.\nIf the clip does not contain a clear self-contained event, the model is instructed\nto output SKIP.\nYou are given:\n- A video clip from a movie.\n- A movie overview for background context only.\nOverview: {movie_overview}\nIMPORTANT: This clip may still be incomplete relative to the full movie. Do\nNOT assume anything outside what is visible in this clip. Do NOT use prior\nknowledge of the movie, characters, or story. Use only what is directly shown.\nTASK: Your task is to generate ONE 5-option multiple-choice question about the\nmain visual event or progression shown in this clip. If the clip does NOT contain\na clear, self-contained action, reaction, reveal, or cause–effect moment that is fully\nshown, output:\nSKIP\nThe question MUST reflect the main development of the clip, not a small detail\nfrom a brief moment. Focus on the most important or climactic visible event.\nDo NOT generate a question if:\n- The moment is routine or transitional\n- The answer depends on events outside this clip\n- It requires guessing thoughts, intentions, or emotions\n- It relies on what happens before or after the clip\nIf uncertain, output:\nSKIP\nRequirements:\n- 1–2 sentence question\n- Answerable using only this clip\n- No “Why” questions\n- No references to before or after the clip\n- No psychological interpretation\n- Focus on clearly visible actions or outcomes\nAll incorrect options must be plausible.\nOutput format:\nQuestion:\n<question>\nA.\nB.\nC.\nD.\nE.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n19\n\nCorrect Answer: <letter>\nRationale:\n<1–2 sentences describing only visible evidence>\n\nTrack B (context-conditioned QA). The Track B prompt introduces an\nexplicit separation between a context window and a target scene. The context\nmay introduce entities or situations, but the correct answer must be visually verifiable in the target scene. The prompt further discourages references to timestamps, dialogue, or outside knowledge to ensure questions remain grounded in\nobservable visual information.\nYou are given a movie video clip and a brief movie overview for background only.\nOverview: {movie_overview}\nThe first {context_len} seconds of the clip are CONTEXT.\nThe remaining part of the clip is the TARGET SCENE.\nThe context may introduce people, objects, or locations that help interpret the\ntarget scene.\nGenerate ONE multiple-choice question (5 options A-E) that requires using the\ncontext to understand what is happening in the target scene.\nKey principle: The answer must be visible in the TARGET SCENE, but the\nCONTEXT should help identify or interpret the object, person, or situation referenced in the question.\nPreferred patterns:\n- An object or person appears in the context, and the question asks about its\nstate, action, or location in the target scene.\n- Something in the target scene is ambiguous unless the viewer remembers the\ncontext.\n- The context introduces an item or situation whose consequence or change\nbecomes visible in the target scene.\nRules:\n- The question must be answerable using only what is visibly shown in the video. The correct answer must be visually verifiable in the TARGET SCENE (after the\nfirst {context_len} seconds).\n- The context should help identify what the question refers to, but should not\ncontain the answer itself.\n- Do not rely on character names, dialogue, subtitles, or outside knowledge.\n- Focus on observable actions, objects, interactions, or spatial relationships.\n- Avoid trivial decorative details that do not affect the scene.\n- Do not ask “Why” questions or infer emotions, intentions, or story meaning.\n- Do not mention numeric timestamps, seconds, or \"the first {context_len}\nseconds\".\n- Do not refer to the video itself (no phrases like “in this clip” or “on screen”).\n\n\f20\n\nS. H. Hahm et al.\n\nThe question MUST reflect the main development of the clip, not a small detail\nfrom a brief moment. Focus on the most important or climactic visible event.\nDo NOT generate a question if:\n- The moment is routine or transitional\n- The answer depends on events outside this clip\n- It requires guessing thoughts, intentions, or emotions\n- It relies on what happens before or after the clip\nIf there is no clear visual moment after the context that connects to something\nintroduced earlier, output:\nSKIP\nOutput format:\nQuestion:\n<question>\nA. <option>\nB. <option>\nC. <option>\nD. <option>\nE. <option>\nCorrect Answer: <letter>\nRationale:\n<1–2 sentences describing only the visible evidence in the target\nscene that confirms the answer>\n\nS10.6\n\nStoryAD-QA Question Answering Prompt\n\nDuring evaluation, we provide the language model with only textual inputs:\nthe question and the corresponding audio descriptions for the scene. The model\nis instructed to select an answer using only the information contained in the\nAD, without the use of external knowledge, prior familiarity with the movie, or\nassumptions about events not described in the AD text. In addition, the model\nis required to produce a short rationale citing explicit evidence from the AD,\nencouraging answers that are grounded in the provided narration.\nTo reduce positional bias, the answer options are randomly shuffled before\nbeing presented to the language model during evaluation.\nYou are given:\n- Audio Descriptions (AD) for a movie scene.\n- A multiple-choice question about that scene.\n\n\fStoryTeller\n\n21\n\nQuestion:\n{question}\nAudio Descriptions (AD):\n{ad_text}\nIMPORTANT: Use only information explicitly stated in the AD text. Do NOT\nuse prior knowledge of the movie. Do NOT assume events outside the AD. Do\nNOT guess characters’ thoughts or intentions unless the AD explicitly states them.\nTASK: Select the best answer (A, B, C, D, or E) based only on the AD.\nOutput format:\nAnswer: <letter>\nRationale:\n<1–2 sentences citing only explicit AD evidence>\n\nReferences\n1. Deng, J., Guo, J., Xue, N., Zafeiriou, S.: Arcface: Additive angular margin loss for\ndeep face recognition. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer\nVision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 4690–4699 (2019)\n2. Kala, D., Khandelwal, E., Tapaswi, M.: What you see is what you ask: Evaluating\naudio descriptions. In: Christodoulopoulos, C., Chakraborty, T., Rose, C., Peng, V.\n(eds.) Proceedings of the Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language\nProcessing (EMNLP). pp. 23496–23518. Association for Computational Linguistics,\nSuzhou, China (Nov 2025). https://doi.org/10.18653/v1/2025.emnlp- main.\n1199, https://aclanthology.org/2025.emnlp-main.1199/\n3. Song, E., Chai, W., Wang, G., Zhang, Y., Zhou, H., Wu, F., Chi, H., Guo, X.,\nYe, T., Zhang, Y., Lu, Y., Hwang, J.N., Wang, G.: Moviechat: From dense token\nto sparse memory for long video understanding. In: Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF\nConference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR). pp. 18221–18232\n(June 2024)\n4. Xie, J., Han, T., Bain, M., Nagrani, A., Varol, G., Xie, W., Zisserman, A.: AutoADZero: A training-free framework for zero-shot audio description. In: Proceedings of\nthe Asian Conference on Computer Vision (ACCV). pp. 2265–2281 (2024)\n\n\f","numLines":343,"startLine":1997,"totalLines":2339}}}
